rememberedPersonSummary.name: Louise  Obern
story:
On the 10th March Louise Obern, 32, passed away. She was a much loved and adored daughter, sister, wife, Mum, friend and physiotherapist.

Louise is, was and will always be remembered for being a breath of fresh air. She was eternally positive, loving, compassionate and utterly selfless in her desire to help and support not only her family and friends but her patients too.

As a Macmillan physiotherapist at Dorchester Hospital she was known for her energy and enthusiasm, with a relentless tenacity to improve the service provision for the cancer patients in the community she served.

Louise’s attention to detail, empathy and patient centered approach was unique, recognizing and supporting her patients individual needs from diagnosis and throughout their journey.

As an UK Ambassador of the Pinc and Steel Foundation she believed in supporting patients through exercise-based therapy. She showed great courage and leadership with the example she set during her own treatment: completing a 5km run with her friends and family.

Louise was a remarkable women and a wonderful person. She was much more than a career women, she was a doting caring and incredible wife (to Chris) and Mummy to their son Reuben.

The love and energy that she brought to her family and their home was incredible. Nothing was too much trouble for her son and husband. Even during her treatment she remained stoic, energetic, positive, focused on the love, affection and support she had for her family.

Louise would always see the choices that life would present, even during the most daunting and difficult of times. Out of such tragedy and sadness she would want there to be an opportunity.

Therefore Chris and Reuben would like you to support in Louise’s memory either Pinc and Steel or Macmillan Cancer UK so the fantastic work that these charities do can continue to support countless therapists in their desire to help patients and their families.

Macmillan UK

Pinc and Steel

story:
SYNETIQ's charity partner is Macmillan Cancer Support, as chosen by its employees. This page has been created to collect donations from the different charity events that will be held throughout 2021. When you donate, JustGiving will send your money directly to Macmillan Cancer Support.

Macmillan offer people with cancer emotional, physical and financial support from the moment they’re diagnosed. When they're diagnosed, their worries become Macmillan's worries and the charity will do whatever it takes to support them. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. 

SYNETIQ is the leading integrated salvage and vehicle recycling company, headquartered in Doncaster. Its mission is to lead the vehicle recycling industry through a focus on innovation and a commitment to doing the right thing.

SYNETIQ processes over 100,000 vehicles each year, on behalf of many of the UK’s leading insurers and fleets, and promotes the 4 'R's - reduce, reuse, remanufacture and recycle.

Find out more at www.SYNETIQ.co.uk

story:
So here we are again, raising money for such an amazing charity who have helped our family in the most darkest of places  - Back in 2019 I ran the landmarks to raise money for Macmillan after my father in law was diagnosed with Bowel Cancer, through the commitment and outstanding work Macmillan do, my father in law is still here with us today! 

I am running the London Landmarks again in 2021 to continue that fundraising as my mother in law is now battling again for the 3rd time in her life Breast Cancer. 

Karen is a BRCA1 Gene carrier and at the young age of just 32 won her fight, she then got another breast cancer in 2013 ages just 49. She underwent chemotherapy and mastectomy of the affected side again she  fought and won her battle!!! 

Sadly, in December 2020 Karen got the devastating  news the cancer was back in the muscle and chest wall of the breast she had removed in 2014. Many years ago as part of the mastectomy they removed the muscle however nowadays this isn’t something they do, so again her fight starts. She has an extremely intense course of chemotherapy which she is currently undergoing and once this is done will undergo a massive operation of yet again another mastectomy including all muscle removal and restructure. 

Karen is a fighter and with  all the support and help from all the staff in the hospital and nurses at Macmillan it makes that fight a little easier.

We raised over £2,200 pounds in 2019 and will continue to try and raise more for such an amazing charity 

Just about 1 in 2 if you have been affected by cancer and the work the Macmillan Cancer Support give us is second to none, so please if you can spare anything, we would all be so very grateful. .

story:
At HOP, we're all about 'partying for a purpose' - and this time it's for the 'Forgotten C' of the pandemic. A terrible illness that the pandemic has made even harder for so many, with over 50,000 cases going undetected this year alone, plus so much treatment postponed due to NHS pressures.

With this livestream, we're wanting to raise awareness to the 'Forgotten C' and get as much money as we can to get cancer services 'Back On Track' 🎼 .

We hope you enjoy our line-up of special guests that take us on a journey across the electronic spectrum from disco, dark disco, tech house, deep house + melodic techno 🚀

Scarlett Lapidus

Beyond The Struttosphere

LIZE

Henri Bergmann

Bushwacka!

story:
Hi! I’m Jamie! I am not a runner. I’ve never been one for fitness in general. So why have a go at Couch to 5K? I know 5k doesn’t seem like a big distance, but I can’t stress enough how unfit I actually am! So I’m starting from the beginning!

Macmillan Cancer Support is very close to my heart. My Mum passed away from cancer in 2012 at the age of 43. To say that destroyed me is an understatement and the help that Macmillan provide is invaluable to families across the country!

I’ve set my target at £250. I hope this is achievable, I hope that I can get your support going forward and I’ll keep everyone updated with my progress as I get closer to running 5k for the first time in my life!

Let’s do this!

story:
In August 2021, I will be taking on the huge challenge of running the London Landmarks Half Marathon.  I have no experience running what. so. ever. In fact, until recently, if you’d of asked me I would have told you that running altogether should be illegal.  However, I have been persuaded, by Macmillan, by what the Charity means to the people around me. By the affects of Cancer and the need for such an amazing charity to be regularly available to those that need it. SO, I have started the Couch to 5k, then I shall do 5-10k and 10-20k until I can run without crying and/or vomiting. I will stand by my friends and hope adrenaline and good-will carry my skinny legs through!

Although Macmillan didn’t get the opportunity to physically support my (Dumpsy) in his late diagnosis of bowel cancer  they were a massive ray of hope for me and my Nana recently in his last days. Their support and understanding was a well needed sense of calm and rational in a hard and confusing time. 

Even now, the Macmillan team still contribute to affect the lives of those I love. I can’t pretend to relate to some of the ways that Cancer has touched some of those closest to me. However, running this Half Marathon, raising donations for Macmillan, is a way for me to support those that my words cannot. I can’t cure cancer! But I CAN put on a wig and run at the back of 100,000 other people wanting to support people that need it. Please donate if you can afford to! If not please share! Love to all, Eden xxx

story:
Sadly I was too late to register for the official South Downs  Challenge but I didn’t want to let this disappointment prevent me completing a personal challenge and raising some money for Macmillan nurses, who are currently providing support to my parents, as they have done with so many others.  

The path is there on my doorstep, I know someone who is patient enough to teach me to read a map and I have an amazing friend, Rachey, who wants to come too, so what’s to stop me?

If you could spare the price of your morning coffee to sponsor me to walk 30 miles of the South Downs Way over 2 days, I’d be very grateful. Every penny will go to support the work of these incredible people. 

Thank you.

story:
I have been busy making Bean Bag Mobile Phone holders to raise money for Macmillan Cancer charity in Northern Ireland.  Just before Christmas 2020, my best friend Carley, was diagnosed with Breast Cancer, which came as a bolt out of the blue for everyone.  Thankfully after successful surgery and subsequent treatment, things are looking positive. Macmillan have been very supportive to Carley and I wanted to be able to assist by raising much needed funds for their work here at home in Northern Ireland.

Being a novice on the sewing machine, this was quite an enjoyable challenge to be able to help and support in some way.  To purchase a Bean Bag Mobile Phone holder I am suggesting a donation of £10 each, with all the proceeds going to Macmillan, to be spent here at home in Northern Ireland.  Please email me once purchased to arrange collection of your Bean Bag on cat1dickson@hotmail.com.

story:
I have decided to have my hair cut off and to donate it to The Little Princess Trust. They make wigs for boys and girls who have lost their hair due to the treatment they are having for cancer. I am hoping to have at least 12" cut off.

I wanted to raise money for my teacher Mr Wood too. He taught me and always made learning fun. He unfortunately lost his fight with cancer in the summer. His family were helped by Macmillan and chose this charity for the fundraising we have done at school.

I am having my hair cut on 28th April and hope I can help both these charities.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Zoe  Davison
story:
Thank you for visiting the page! 

We lost a beautiful soul in the amazing Zoe. Zoe has a long battle with cancer and she fought so hard. Zoe had such a kind heart and was amazing to our family. She was so welcoming and just an incredible person inside an out. Her loss is devastating to anyone who knew her as she was a complete ray of sunshine no matter what she faced. She always had a smile for everyone. 

My incredibly brave friend Roz is also facing her own cancer battle currently. She is an amazing woman who dedicates her life to helping others as a speech and language therapist. She has the greatest laugh and sense of humour and I'm proud to call her my friend. 

We are aiming to walk 100+ miles over the Easter holidays to raise some pennies for Macmillan to help those who are facing this awful illness. The kids are taking part too and want to do their bit to add to the total (they both may have little legs but have massive hearts!) 

We wanted to help the great work that MacMillan do to support people by helping them as much as we can 

I know this year has been tough for everyone but any donation no matter how small will be so greatly appreciated 


Thank you for reading our sorry and thank you for any donation you may be able to give 


Ali, Ellis, Stacey and Lucy xx

story:
Next Monday (29th of March) I will run a solo marathon and attempt to break 3h, which is a magical barrier for amateur marathoners. On this day I will be exactly 42.195 years old, so it seems a good day to race!

Please support me by supporting others and donating for Macmillan Cancer Support.

Last year I trained for Edinburgh Marathon in May, but it got cancelled. I tried to continue my training anyway, but the weather and lockdown did not allow for it. Now I have spent last months on proper training and missed out or failed on only a few of the sessions. 4 weeks ago I raced solo a half marathon and set a new PB of 1:25:29, which is promising. So I know I’m close to 2:59, but how close? I will have to find out. There is magic in this distance, maybe demons on last kilometres, plus whatever the weather brings – wind, warmth, humidity or dust. Or all of it.

Whatever the result will be I am already grateful that I could have trained for these months – free to run outside and without any injury. Plus, I haven’t been so consistent and fast in running ever!

story: On 1 April 2021, we will mark our 50th Anniversary in the Industry and to celebrate such an auspicious moment, TBG employees (330 at present) will attempt to undertake their biggest challenge yet, in the hope of raising £24,901 for Macmillan. Cancer seems to affect us all in some way and as any person with cancer knows, a cancer diagnosis also affects family members and friends. Sometimes, the complex feelings and lifestyle changes caused by cancer and its treatment become as overwhelming for others as they are for the person affected. This is why Macmillan Cancer Support workers are so important. They consist of millions of people affected by cancer, supporters, professionals, volunteers, and campaigners and they all have one thing in common their care and support for people living with cancer. So we at TBG will make the daunting 24,901 miles to support Macmillan how far will you go?

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
CBRE are proud to partner Macmillan Cancer Support.

Living with cancer can be devastating at the best of times, but even harder as a result of the recent pandemic.  At Macmillan, we talk to people affected by cancer every day and for many, issues with money and mental health such as stress and depression, are their biggest worry.

Our partnership focuses on tackling financial hardship and loneliness together, helping Macmillan develop their telephone, online and virtual support services and to help thousands more people with much needed financial and emotional support.

The CBRE partnership is going to be more important than ever before, to help Macmillan do whatever it takes to support every single person living with cancer.

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
To celebrate our 40th year, we aim to raise £40k for Macmillan Cancer Support by walking over 40 miles from our Head Office in Coventry to Corby later this year. In our 40th year in the UK we are calling on the support of our employees, their families and our partners to help this wonderful charity who offered unwavering support to a valued employee and friend of GEFCO UK, Denise Panter, and her family during her fight against cancer last year. The past 12 months have been extremely challenging for all and the pandemic has placed restrictions upon what we can do to acknowledge our time in the UK. So, we’d like to brighten up our summer and celebrate this milestone by raising much needed funds for our chosen charity partner and invest further in our employee’s wellbeing by encouraging as many who are willing, to walk the distance with us.


My story - 

So as some of you will be aware, in 2020 I faced my own battle with cancer. In September I was diagnosed with testicular cancer and although I seen myself as relatively fit and healthy, with age on my side, I was still left with the worry of wondering how bad it was and what treatment etc I would need. It was then I had the realisation that it can literally happen to any of us and it’s sad that most of us now, know someone who has or has had cancer. Now I was really lucky that mine was found early and after being removed, I only had to go through one count of chemotherapy and touch wood I am now fine, with just regular check ups for the next few years. 

I said in 2021 I would like to raise as much money as possible to help support the cause and COVID dependant, I have a few things I would like to do this year. The first one is taking part in a 40 mile walk on the weekend of the 9th July.

I would appreciate any donations you can kindly offer. I know lots of you have supported me in charity events before and lots of us are busy supporting charities all the time, but no donation is too small and a massive help to a great cause. 


Thanks in advance

Hi, I am Sam from Mumma's Kitchen Delights. I have recently started my own business and wanted to help a charity through my business creations, therefore, I will be holding monthly raffles of my chocolate creations at the local market and online for you to participate in and donate to my charity. There are 3 charities that are close to mine and my families hearts, "MIND", "Macmillan Cancer Support" and the "Stroke Association". Online donations can be made to the charity of your choice, any offline raffle ticket sales made at the market will be split between all 3 charities. Please support all 3 charities, every little bit makes a big difference.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
SUEZ are proud to be partnering with Macmillan Cancer Support.

There are currently 3 million people living with cancer in the UK, with someone receiving a cancer diagnosis every two minutes. We know that one in two people in the UK will experience a cancer diagnosis in their lifetime. 

For more than 100 years Macmillan has been there for people with cancer when they needed them most.  Today is no exception! 

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.  

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing physical, financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

story:
Our amazing dad was recently diagnosed with cancer late last year and has been battling bravely ever since. 

Macmillan have been a fantastic support and I would like to help them as much as possible. 

I will be running as many miles as I can from now till the end of April 2021. I would encourage all my family and friends to join in and see how many miles we can all reach together. 

Please send me a screenshot of your walk/run/cycle via what's app or text message which shows how many miles/km you have ran or cycled. If you don't have my number, private message me on Facebook and I'll give you my number. It really doesn't matter how many miles/km you do but the more the better! I will collate the amount of miles we have hit and share the total. 

Any donations during these tough times would be greatly appreciated for such a great cause.

story: On 1 April 2021, we will mark our 50th Anniversary in the Industry and to celebrate such an auspicious moment, TBG employees (330 at present) will attempt to undertake their biggest challenge yet, in the hope of raising £24,901 for Macmillan. Cancer seems to affect us all in some way and as any person with cancer knows, a cancer diagnosis also affects family members and friends. Sometimes, the complex feelings and lifestyle changes caused by cancer and its treatment become as overwhelming for others as they are for the person affected. This is why Macmillan Cancer Support workers are so important. They consist of millions of people affected by cancer, supporters, professionals, volunteers, and campaigners and they all have one thing in common  their care and support for people living with cancer. So we at TBG will make the daunting 24,901 miles to support Macmillan  how far will you go?

story:
CBRE are proud to partner Macmillan Cancer Support.

Living with cancer can be devastating at the best of times, but even harder as a result of the recent pandemic.  At Macmillan, we talk to people affected by cancer every day and for many, issues with money and mental health such as stress and depression, are their biggest worry.

Our partnership focuses on tackling financial hardship and loneliness together, helping Macmillan develop their telephone, online and virtual support services and to help thousands more people with much needed financial and emotional support.

The CBRE partnership is going to be more important than ever before, to help Macmillan do whatever it takes to support every single person living with cancer.

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
CBRE are proud to partner Macmillan Cancer Support.

Living with cancer can be devastating at the best of times, but even harder as a result of the recent pandemic.  At Macmillan, we talk to people affected by cancer every day and for many, issues with money and mental health such as stress and depression, are their biggest worry.

Our partnership focuses on tackling financial hardship and loneliness together, helping Macmillan develop their telephone, online and virtual support services and to help thousands more people with much needed financial and emotional support.

The CBRE partnership is going to be more important than ever before, to help Macmillan do whatever it takes to support every single person living with cancer.

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

story:
Thank you for supporting my fundraising for Macmillan Cancer Support. Macmillan provide physical, financial and moral support to people with cancer. 

I have my own experience of cancer, having been diagnosed with a malignant melanoma shortly before my 60th birthday. I'm lucky to be fit and well now, having received great treatment from the team at Southampton General Hospital, which includes a Macmillan Information and Support Centre.

I'm retiring from regular employment at the end of March and marking that event with this fundraising effort (cycling 400 miles in April), which will be a genuine stretch for me.

Check my progress on Strava.

Thanks again for your donation.

Drew

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Ron Lee
story:
Ron was diagnosed with cancer 18 years ago and eventually lost his long battle with the disease in March 2021.

He was a man of faith and never stopped fighting, holding onto his faith and remaining positive throughout.

Ron was my best friend and soulmate, a loving husband and wonderful dad to our three children. 

In his memory we are raising money for the Macmillan Cancer Trust who cared for Ron towards the end of his journey and were also a huge support for me and the family as we walked this road alongside Ron.

We invite you to make a donation to this wonderful charity in memory of Ron should you wish, so they can continue to support other families as they negotiate their cancer journey. 

Thank you

rememberedPersonSummary.name: William French
story:
Thank you for hopping onto my Just Giving page!

I understand that 2020 has made money a struggle for a lot of people so the fact that you’re even here considering donating to my crazy Skydiving cause is amazing! Thank you!

I’m raising money for MacMillan Cancer Support as my grandad passed away on 16th March 2021 and their support in the run up to his final days on this earth was phenomenal. I don’t know whether my grandparents just got lucky with the amazing MacMillan nurse, Tracey or if they’re all so wonderful but she truly was a light in the darkest of times and made sure that my grandads final hours were the most comfortable and supported he could possibly have.

My grandad was all about helping others wherever he could. Nothing was too much effort and he always made sure his family was safe, supported and we always came first no matter what. To say he was one of a kind is an understatement and the hurt we feel from his loss is indescribable.

There were a number of charities that I wanted to do this for including Marie Curie, Barnsley Hospice and Prostate Cancer UK but Tracey from MacMillan really did show us that star quality when it came to genuine care and love for her patients and families. I think my grandad would agree that this was the right choice.

There’s no confirmed date yet but my Skydive will be taking place towards the end of May so I’ve got two months to raise my goal of £500 - I considered doing some walking or jogging around but hey, that just isn’t my style! I wanted to bring some excitement and craziness to the cause and give people something to REALLY donate for!

A little goes a long way in helping me reach my target so I honestly do appreciate every penny donated. I couldn’t just sit around waiting for the grief to pass, I wanted to do something to continue making my grandad proud. It’s all for him.

For William xx
title: Bethany's Skydive for Grandad

story: On 1 April 2021, we will mark our 50th Anniversary in the Industry and to celebrate such an auspicious moment, TBG employees (330 at present) will attempt to undertake their biggest challenge yet, in the hope of raising £24,901 for Macmillan. Cancer seems to affect us all in some way and as any person with cancer knows, a cancer diagnosis also affects family members and friends. Sometimes, the complex feelings and lifestyle changes caused by cancer and its treatment become as overwhelming for others as they are for the person affected. This is why Macmillan Cancer Support workers are so important. They consist of millions of people affected by cancer, supporters, professionals, volunteers, and campaigners and they all have one thing in common  their care and support for people living with cancer. So we at TBG will make the daunting 24,901 miles to support Macmillan  how far will you go?

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit Lyn's JustGiving page.

We are asking for donations to Macmillan Cancer Support as Lyn requested for donations to them because of the sustained support they gave during the time she needed them.

Lyn was always helping others, it was second nature to her.  Even throughout her suffering she was there to support and raise a smile.  If the situation called for someone to be there to help, she was there for whatever was needed.  Always a giver, very rarely a taker, fun loving, loyal and a fighter.

Lyn was a friend to so many people.  She will be missed by the children and team at 1st Cheshunt Scout Group and the many friends in the groups she was part of; previous work friends, dancing, walking netball, Trefoil and Slimming World.

Lyn was a loving mother, daughter and sister and will forever be in our hearts. 💚

Hello, 

I'm challenging myself to do 4,500 squats during the month of April. I am doing this for my Dad, who has suffered over the years with different forms of Cancer and has come out fighting everytime which makes me so proud, but also for every women, man and child that has or is going through some form of Cancer. This past year has especially been difficult for cancer patients to have any treatment or appointments due to Covid. But we can help raise money and get the ball rolling again.

I will add a document of me doing the squats so you can see I am actually doing it or just check out my ass next time you see me lol.. Starts the 1st April..

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. I would like to raise money for a worthy cause in memory of my mum Joan. 

Mum was a kind and extremely intelligent woman who loved reading, cooking and bird watching. Her friends described her as an inspirational teacher and true friend. She was passionate about politics, democracy and doing the right thing. Mum also had an adventurous side and enjoyed a good social get together.  She will be sorely missed as a loving wife, mother and grandma.

story: On 1 April 2021, we will mark our 50th Anniversary in the Industry and to celebrate such an auspicious moment, TBG employees (330 at present) will attempt to undertake their biggest challenge yet, in the hope of raising £24,901 for Macmillan. Cancer seems to affect us all in some way and as any person with cancer knows, a cancer diagnosis also affects family members and friends. Sometimes, the complex feelings and lifestyle changes caused by cancer and its treatment become as overwhelming for others as they are for the person affected. This is why Macmillan Cancer Support workers are so important. They consist of millions of people affected by cancer, supporters, professionals, volunteers, and campaigners and they all have one thing in common their care and support for people living with cancer. So we at TBG will make the daunting 24,901 miles to support Macmillan how far will you go?

story:
We have found out that we are, once again, going through the fight. My (soon-to-be, should-already-be) mother-in-law has recently found out that we will need to start treatment for cancer.

She will crush this, but it won't be the easiest time for her, so in my own, small way, I wanted to sacrifice something in solidarity. Along the way I hope to raise money for the charity that has already, and will continue to support Shirley, and those closest to her.

So my sacrifice is that for the month of April, I will drink nothing but water. So no beer o'clock, no whisky on the weekends and worst of all, no constant stream of coffee.

A word from Macmillan:

At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising for Macmillan.

I aim to raise as much as possible to go towards vital services this charity provides to all who need their support.  Cancer has affected a few of my family members in the past and this disease does not discriminate regarding age or gender. 

I would not have believed anyone if they had told me I would be walking every day during lockdown.  But, like many, I started walking to avoid feeling locked up.  

Initially I walked once a week from March to July 2020 locally around the woods with one friend at a time.  Thereafter, walks were almost daily and progressed to other suggested walks which were longer.  From over 2+ mile walks to 5+, 7+ and more recently 9+ mile walks and up really steep hills.  It took a lot of push during the progressive months especially during the rain and during the time it snowed. 

At the beginning of February 2021 a friend suggested walking for Macmillan.  Perfect....everything happens for a reason - right?  So currently we are practicing more regularly on steep hills (there are lots of them around here) and longer walks which have become easier. 

Some of the pictures I took during my walks over the months prior to knowing I would be taking on this challenge has been uploaded above in the media gallery.  I will add to this as time goes on. 

The team and I are looking forward to the Yorkshire Dales Macmillan challenge.  I am glad the past few months have become the training ground towards such a good cause. 

Donating through JustGiving is fast and secure.  All donations are sent directly to the charity via my Macmillan (JustGiving) web page.

charity.description:
The nation’s leading first aid charity.
Every year, more than 400,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes.
Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
St John Ambulance has been running as a charity for over 900 years, we have a proud history of saving lives and caring for communities.

Help us ease the strain during the COVID-19 outbreak. Since the start of the pandemic our dedicated St John Ambulance volunteers have been relieving pressure on our NHS by boosting the health response in communities across the country.

St John are proud to be working alongside ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country and to have developed partnerships to deliver many small-scale local healthcare projects. Cambridgeshire volunteers have been supporting Addenbrookes Hospital since January 2020, where they have given over 8,500 hours of their time. They were the first St John volunteers to trial hospital support, which rapidly moved to Covid-19 support.

We’re drawing on our longstanding expertise to support the vaccination programme, empowering people with lifesaving clinical skills and the confidence to use them, every day. Eventually, more than 30,000 volunteers will support around 100 vaccination centres all over England. In Cambridgeshire, our volunteers are supporting five vaccination centres, the second largest deployment across the country.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As part of of my Duke Of Edinburgh Bronze award volunteering section I am supporting and raising money for the charity St Johns Ambulance. If you don’t know who they are then I will explain. St Johns Ambulance is a first aid and ambulance service charity that spreads across a whopping 40 countries. They play a big role in the NHS which is very critical in todays current climate. By supporting them you are helping this service and could save many lives.

I have challenged myself to a 30 mile route which requires me to go down huge drops and up monstrous climbs accumulating 3,000 feet of climbing across the cotswolds. This is a real challenge as I am not an experienced rider - I am a goalkeeper and so the extent of my fitness requires me to dive from one goal post to another!

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
British Heart Foundation is the biggest independent funder of cardiovascular research in the UK. Their continued research has had a positive impact on both my grandads but sadly lost one of them, my uncle and millions of people around the world.  

The British Heart Foundation is funding life saving research to help end heartbreak for the seven million people in the UK living with cardiovascular disease. For over 50 years it has pioneered research that has transformed the lives of people living with heart and circulatory conditions and has been pivotal to offering vital treatments that are changing the fight against heart disease.

The money raised for this stream goes directly to the charity which you are doing via this page. 

PLEASE DONATE  any amount of money that you wish as together hopefully we can reach my target or better if we can. 

Thank you and I really appreciate it. 

Josh

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Myself and a few friends are challenging ourselves to complete the London to Brighton Off Road Mountain Bike Ride. 60+ miles of hills, trails and mud!

After getting back into Mountain Biking during lockdown, I was looking at off road cycling routes and discovered this event. As soon as I saw the charity involved was The British Heart Foundation, I knew I had to sign up. Thankfully it didn't take much to convince a few friends to join in.

Heart and circulatory diseases still kill 1 in 4 in the UK. The British Heart Foundation helps research cures and treatments and offer support to affected families. Thanks to this research a couple of my friends are still with us today, Dads who can still hug their kids and families. So please donate, every pound you give will help save lives.

Thanks!

Thanks for visiting my page. Many of you will remember that I completed this challenge in 2015, and this should have been 5 years on, but Covid put a spanner in that plan! So her I am, with knees 6 years older taking it on again.  You’d think someone my age would know better  

It’s a short 100km hike down to the seaside, stopping only for short breaks every few km . It was definitely the most challenging thing I’ve ever done, and I can’t tell you how much donations spurred me on in the early hours of the morning  

I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

eventName: One half marathon per month for a year!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Since 2016 I have run in The Great Scottish Run; Glasgow half marathon, raising vital funds for charity. In 2020 I had booked to ‘up the challenge level’ and was all set to complete both Glasgow and Edinburgh half marathons on consecutive weekends. Unfortunately due to current worldly circumstances, these events were cancelled. 

Cue a change of plans!! 

Taking things up a notch again, beginning in June 2020, I decided to run a half marathon every month for a year. Bearing in mind I would usually have to put in some considerable run training before such a one off event, this new challenge meant I would need to keep up this level of grit and discipline for a full year. The winter months especially worrying me due to health conditions in my hands and arms which are heightened with the cold. Still.... the goal was to push through; a challenge is not a challenge without pushing yourself. 

As someone who could not run the length of herself and had little to no self belief not all that long ago,  I am very proud of my progress in my own health and fitness to date - physically and mentally. If I can inspire just one other person to have the belief in them self that they can feel better, then I’d be very happy. 

I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. This charity means a lot personally to me and my family. They have helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people still lose their lives. 

Every pound helps towards creating new treatments and discovering new cures, so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
Hello, 

I'm raising money by raffling an original pencil drawing I have recently completed of Tony Soprano (portrayed by the late James Gandolfini). 

All proceeds will go directly to the British Heart Foundation in memory of a good friend of mine (Will Coogan) who recently passed away. Will was in the final year of his PHD which was being funded by the British Heart Foundation. The Sopranos was one of Will's favourite TV shows and it seemed fitting to raffle the drawing off in Will's memory. 

T&Cs:

- Each £5 donation equates to one entry into the raffle.

- There is no limit on the amount of entries you can have but all donations are to be made in multiples of 5 (i.e. 1 entry = £5; 2 entries = £10; 5 entries = £25 etc.).

- Gift Aid cannot be claimed due to this being a raffle.

- Please make sure to include your name when donating. 

- The raffle will run for two weeks ending on Easter Sunday (4 April 2021) at 19:00.

- The winner will be announced on Instagram Live (account: @artbyjft) at 19:00 on 4 April 2021. I will use the wheelofnames.com service to pick the winner at random. 

- The winner will receive the original drawing (framed) signed by me (JFT). The drawing is A4 sized.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Mark Ayliffe
story:
We are excited to introduce our first TQtogether charity event in aid of British Heart Foundation, 60 miles in 60 days and in memory of our colleague, Mark Ayliffe.

In late 2020, we were extremely saddened to hear of Mark’s passing. He was a much-loved colleague not only to our Cambridge team, but to the Company as a whole. The 60 miles in 60 days event has been set up to raise money for The British Heart Foundation, which has been nominated by Mark’s family.

This event encourages staff to walk, run, cycle or swim the 60-mile distance over the 60 days. Staff are to start their 60-mile journey on 1st April 2021 and complete the distance by 30th May 2021. 

TQtogether are raising money for the British Heart Foundation and we would be so grateful for your support.

British Heart Foundation
The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. With your support, the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

William Ham, Fundraising Manager for the BHF said “We are enormously grateful to everyone at TrustQuay for not only nominating the BHF as one of their chosen charities this year but also for showing such interest in taking part in the 60:60 physical challenge. The Covid-19 pandemic has had a devastating impact on our investment into life-saving research. TrustQuay’s timely support, when so many others have cancelled their fundraising plans, is particularly appreciated. We know that nearly half of people that died of Covid-19 also suffered from heart and circulatory conditions, so there has never been a more important time to back the BHF."

For more information about the TQtogether initiative, please visit our page:  
https://blog.trustquay.com/tqtogether-giving-a-helping-hand-a-trustquay-initiative

TQtogether - A TrustQuay initiative to give a helping hand

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Andrew  Flanagan
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am Andrew’s little sister, and as a family we have set up this page in memory of ‘our Andrew’ as we have had so many ask how they can show their love and respects to him. We are not having flowers at the funeral so any donation, big or small to this charity would be grateful. If anything, to raise awareness of heart attacks in such young individuals. 

On 12th March my life got turned upside down and will never be the same again. My dear brother: son and husband had a heart attack and unfortunately didn’t recover and sadly passed away on 17th March. We are immensely proud of Andrew’s decision to donate his organs, who the hospital all found matches for. Andrew was a fighter and hung on that little longer so unable to follow his wishes fully, albeit, some would be able to be passed on and used for those in need.

Andrew was my brother, he was my first ever friend, my protector. I know he will still be looking down on me looking after me. I promise to always speak of you to your nephew and niece who adore you. We are in awe of you Andrew and the amazing lovable gentle giant you were, and the strong beautiful wife you loved so much and left behind.

I know you have gone but you will live on through us all. Forever in our hearts. I will love you forever, Lucy - your little sister

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
It is now 20 years since I first developed Atrial Fibrillation and I came across the BHF and 3 years since I had my Sudden Cardiac Arrest. During this time I personally have found their information services incredibly helpful and I have also used their Cardiac Nurse Phone line whom I have found most knowledgeable. During lockdown I have also re-visited their DVD for Cardiac Rehab which has been most beneficial. 

This year BHF are celebrating 60 years of life saving research. My understanding is that in cases like mine (ie I had my SCA in Mile 25 of a Trail Marathon and had CPR administered by fellow runners, and a recent study in Warwick showed that about 5 in a 100 people who have an OOH SCA arrive at Hospital alive and of those many will struggle to make it out of Hospital without some issues as the brain will have been starved of oxygen whilst "down" (ie unconscious) . About 50% die as there are no bystanders and many of the others as the bystanders don't know what to do. Hence I went along to a series of CPR Training sessions with BHF & BBC Radio Suffolk to say you can save a life by knowing how to do CPR. My blog of my journey has been reproduced in Paul Swindell's book, Life after Sudden Cardiac Arrest. I will re-tell sections on facebook for those interested.

As we gradually ease out of lockdown, and begin to enjoy some Spring sunshine, this is the perfect time to focus on improving our health and wellbeing. The British Heart Foundation turns 60 this year and we wanted to mark the occasion. With support from Active Suffolk, we want to encourage as many people in Suffolk to take on a ‘60’ themed challenge. For some, it could be completing 60 miles (100K) during the month of April (30 days) which is equates to roughly 2miles/3K per day. For others, it could be committing to 60 minutes of relaxation every day, or undertaking 60 minutes of gentle activity, or 60 minutes of gardening. Whatever your ‘60’ challenge is, we want you to feel part of a community who can encourage, inspire and support one another.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Gus  Macdonald
story:
Thank you for visiting my page. I’m raising money for the British Heart Foundation and would be very grateful for your support.
Our journey began over 15 years ago when my father in law Gus had his first heart attack age 67.
He had to retire from an active working life in forestry, now on medication and leading a more sedentary life, but every day was a blessing for us all.

Over the next 14 years, there were a few smaller heart attacks but he recovered with medication and determination and enough to keep his hand in on the occasional woodworking project.

September 2020 Gus took a turn for the worst. His failing heart unable to function well enough and fluid was building up almost ‘drowning him from the inside out’
The family were called as his heart went into uncontrollable tachycardia which meant it could have given up at any moment.
He was treated in hospital over the next month but due to covid restrictions only Violet, my mother in law was allowed to visit.
The separation from home and his family was taking it’s toll on Gus.

Finally he was stabilised enough to be discharged back home to the care of his family as no further treatment would be successful.

As we knew we were on borrowed time we formed a ‘Macdonald bubble’ forsaking allowable interactions with other family & friends to enable we kept Gus safe. This sacrifice allowed us to spend as much time enjoying, loving and caring for him and supporting Vi who had taken on the role as his full time carer.

Gus & Vi had been married 58 years. She was the most patient and dedicated carer, tending tirelessly to his every need, day and night.

His face light up every time a member of the family appeared, especially the grandkids & great grandkids.

We were encouraged with odd days he was able to make soup & bake almost thinking our time together might be extended. Sadly taking us all by surprise early February Gus became very poorly.
Knowing the end was near the family stayed by his side for 4 days, loving and caring for him, holding his hand and at times each other up too.

The end was peaceful surrounded by his loving family, where he wanted to be.

If our donations can help save or prolong someone’s life so their family can hold on to a loved one for a bit longer that would be priceless.

Thank you for your kindness

Liz

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I have set myself the challenge of running 100 miles (161km) in the month of April, in the hopes of raising money for my chosen charity, British Heart Foundation. I already run regularly, however this will be by far the most mileage I have covered in such a short space of time. It will average out at around 5.4km each day for 30 days. 

Lockdown has been an awful time for all of us and it has had detrimental effects on my motivation and mental health in general. Setting myself a challenge like this will keep me fit both physically and mentally, whilst raising money and awareness for such a great cause. 

The British Heart Foundation raises awareness for heart and circulatory diseases, because of this, it is a cause which I feel emotionally attached to:

April is the birth month of my Dad, David, who sadly passed away when i was just 11 years old. He underwent a heart transplant, but unfortunately passed away after picking up a post operative infection and being unable to fight back. I want to do this, not only in memory of my Dad, but also for everyone else out there who may be suffering with cardiac related issues. 

Around 7.6 million people are living with heart and circulatory diseases today. Any donation made to the British Heart Foundation will help further research into the risk factors that cause these heart and circulatory diseases, vital for bringing this upsetting number down.

Thank you for taking the time to read my story and any donation whatsoever is massively appreciated.

Benny X

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
60 years of saving lives, 60 years of breakthroughs and we are not stopping now.

This year the British Heart Foundation celebrates it's 60th year in what has been our most challenging year yet. Now we want you to be part of #team60!

Together with the support of our volunteers, groups, clubs and corporate partners, we have been part of pioneering breakthroughs like heart transplants and pacemakers, stents and clot busting drugs - and our goals for the decades ahead are even more ambitious. Cures for inherited heart diseases, radically improved treatments for stroke, ways to stop vascular dementia in its tracks, and of course, recovering from the brutal blow that is the Covid-19 pandemic - our work and your support is more vital than ever. 

We are calling on all of you across the West Midlands to help us reach our goal of £60,000 one step at a time. When we reach £600 we will shout about our best contributors on our BHF West Midlands Facebook page, then again at £6000 and at our £60,000 total.

Whether you raise £10, £100 or £1000 you will be helping us #beatheartbreakforever.

Thank you from Karen, Donna and Ashleigh (BHF West Midlands)

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Dennis Hemmings
story:
In April I will be running 2 miles every day. This may not seem alot but those who know me they will understand how hard this will be for me.

A while back I lost my Grandad to an aortic aneurysm.  BHF-funded researchers have recently discovered four new genes which are linked to the condition. They’re starting a new piece of research to find out more about what role these genes play in the speed at which aneurysms grow, and which common medications, if any, might be able to slow down the growth of the aneurysm, and if other factors are involved.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

eventName: Great Guide Dogs Virtual Tea Party
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
We're supporting Guide Dogs with a Virtual Tea Party.  Invite your friends and family to join us on Saturday 17th April at 2.30pm.

“I was 16 when I found out I had a brain tumour and lost most of my sight. I stopped wanting to go out or see anyone. The streets were so busy, I would panic. The only place I felt safe was at home. When I contacted Guide Dogs they gave me loads of help and advice. It was a huge relief. They taught me how to use a white cane and I started to get my confidence and life back. When my guide dog Katie arrived, she changed everything. I could go out – to the gym, shopping, see my friends – things I hadn’t been able to do since discovering the brain tumour. She’s unleashed a whole new version of life for me.”
Ella, 21, and guide dog Katie.

The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service

rememberedPersonSummary.name: John O'connell
story:
Not long ago, I said goodbye to a friend and an incredible human, John O'Connell, who sadly died at only 38 years old after a brave year-long battle with leukemia. John was one of the most genuine, caring and warm-hearted people that I have ever had the pleasure of knowing. John was selfless in his endeavours, always putting others first and he is a true inspiration to us all. The world would be a brighter place if there were more people like John in it however his spirit lives on and he can continue to positively impact the world through the actions that we take. 

John was a strong advocate of The Trussell Trust (a charity helping food banks) and Guide Dogs therefore I will be raising money for fantastic causes as John would have done.

To honour John's memory, I will be aiming to walk/jog/run/hobble 100 miles in 24 hours starting on the morning of Thursday 15th April and (hopefully) finishing a day later on Friday 16th April. 

If you are interested in the route, it will be two 50 mile loops around the villages of Northamptonshire. 

Link: https://www.plotaroute.com/route/1478190

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Sally White
story:
We are sending donations to Guide Dogs for the Blind as both Mum and Dad supported the charity throughout their lives.  They were passionate to provide someone to live their life to the full with the help of a furry friend!!!

As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: William (Billy) Twine
story:
My Dad, William "Billy" Twine sadly passed away on 4th March 2021, he was 88 years old.

He thought that flowers were a waste of money so as a family we decided to set up a couple of Just Giving pages where people could make a donation to one of two charities, rather than send flowers, Guide Dogs or Alzheimer's Society.

This page is for the Guide Dogs and we chose this charity as every time their advert came on t.v. my Dad would always say, "that's the only charity worth giving money to". So we've set up this page in his memory.

If you wish to do so please donate whatever you can.

*********

As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

eventName: South Bristol Guide Dogs Charity Quiz
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Are you an avid quizzer? Can you be found glued to the TV watching quiz shows? Are you a general knowledge expert?

We’re hosting a virtual pub quiz to raise money in aid of Guide Dogs. Every pound we raise will support someone with sight loss to feel less alone and isolated, now and in the future.

How to take part

To sign up for the quiz, email Southbristol-guidedogs@hotmail.com by Thursday 8 April 2021 at 5pm. Please include your team name, we’ll use that to track scores and announce the top team on the night.

Donations

It’s free to attend the quiz, after all we could all do with a bit of fun right now. We invite you to make a voluntary donation towards our target of raising at least £250 on the night.

Instead of a round of team drinks down your local, your donation of £15, £10, or £5 could help make a difference to people living with sight loss.

eventName: Tilly's 30 Miles in a Day Cycle Challenge
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
We need your help!

Our very own little pocket rocket, has set herself the target of cycling a 30 mile round trip, from Budleigh Salterton to the Guide Dogs office in Exeter. Not bad for a newly turned 7 Year old!

Since the first lockdown she has been desperate to raise money for a deserving cause. Her love of dogs (especially Labradors) and the amazing work that the Guide Dogs do, easily lead her to her chosen charity!

On the 1st of May Tilly will set out on the mammoth journey to Exeter along the cycle way, travelling through Exmouth, Lympstone, Exton, Topsham, Countess Wear and Marsh Barton, until she reaches the offices of the Guide Dogs. She will then head back along the same route to return home to Budleigh!

Your support and sponsorship mean the world to Tilly! Every penny donated will really encourage her to achieve the goal of raising as much money as possible, for such a wonderful charity.

A note form the Guide Dogs: As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK. It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

Thank you so much for taking the time to find out what is Tilly planning!

Alexis, Andrew and Tilly xxx

story:
I was unaware that every six minutes in the UK, one more person loses their sight, so that's why the work of the Guide Dogs Association is so important. 


A Guide Dog gives people back their freedom and independence, as well as bringing a wonderful new friend and companion into their lives.  As a dog owner, I know how special that bond can be.


Watch out for social media posts for details of how to join me for tea.  If you can't join in, then if you could spare the cost of a cuppa and a cake, then a donation would be greatly appreciated.  Thank you. xx

story:
Join the World's Biggest Tea Party

On Wednesday 21 April we’re celebrating National Tea Day in style and inviting everyone to help us smash our Guinness World Records title for the ‘World’s Biggest Virtual Tea Party’! 

It’s really easy to take part in the record attempt – simply go to our Facebook event, click ‘Going’ and post your tea selfie between 3pm to 4pm. 

Post your selfies from your virtual tea parties, from your work cuppa breaks, from your sofas, back gardens - with your family or with your pets, we’d love to see you all!  If circumstances allow, please consider donating the price of your cuppa on the day and help support our life-changing services

https://fb.me/e/3IwveOYsy 

As you know from previous fundraising, my grandma and uncle were left blind by glaucoma and my mum  had emergency eye surgery during lockdowns to save her eyesight.  So this is a charity close to my heart 

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story:
Hello all, 

My name is Nora.

I have completed this walk in the last 2 years for Guide Dogs and I will walk again this year! My challenge is in the last week of May, hopefully by than we will be allowed to go back to our normal lifes but if not, I will compleate this in our home (even if I need to walk up and down in our living room all day) 😊. 

 I am taking part in the sponsored walk that's good for the sole! 

In my life dogs always played an important role. My first dog teached me to walk, looked after me, protected me. When she passed away, I knew she never be forgotten. Since than I learned so much from dogs. I learned how to be patience, I learned unconditional love. 

So, I felt it is time for me to do something and got involved with this charity event so I can help people experience all the good things what comes with having a dog as your helper, companion, friend, family, guide.  

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

 The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Go on  help me knock my socks off! 

Thank you.

story:
Hey everyone, its that time of year again where I am looking for your help to raise money for Guide Dogs. As you know I got Flynn in November of last year and I cant explain how much he has changed my life. It’s not just the practical/obvious things he has helped with like walking to school, walking at night, shopping and the list could go on. He has also helped me walk around the shops with a little less anxiety, a little less embarrassed about myself and I now am learning to walk with my head held high because of him. I also had the BEST couch I could of ever asked for, so this fundraising isn’t just for the dogs its also for the trainers who put their time into these incredible dogs, its for the boarders that open there homes to the dogs. So please, I know I have asked you before but I need your help again. I am planning to do 10,000 steps with Flynn and raise as much as possible. Thank you for taking your time to read this story. This is just the beginning for me and Flynn. 

 Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. Go on - help me knock my socks off!

story:
Hey! 

As a dog Walker, this is the perfect way of raising money for a good cause! We have a special guide dog that comes with us on our walks called Nick. We hope that any money raised will make more Nicks in the world!! 🐾

Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. Go on - help me knock my socks off!
title: I'm walking my socks off for Guide Dogs!

story:
I'm taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole! I will be stepping it up in my chosen week this May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs!

My Mum always wanted to support this charity, and I want to do what I can to help those that cannot see the things that I can. 

 The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. Go on - help me knock my socks off!

story:
What better way to help raise money for the Guide Dogs than doing what I love best; walking my socks off!

I will be stepping it up; more than usual, this May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs and also donating a percentage from each of my dog walks that week. Any additional donations would be amazing!

The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog.  

Go on - help me knock my socks off!

story: I'm taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole! I will be stepping it up in my chosen week this May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs! My target steps is going to be 30,000 steps over my chosen week! Guide dogs is a cause very close to heart! When my uncle became blind Guide Dogs help him find a wonderful dog called Quincey. Quincey is the most amazing dog and is soon coming up for retirement as a Guide Dog. When this happens guide dogs will help my Uncle in finding another Guide Dogs that is suitable for him needs! The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. Go on - help me knock my socks off!

story:
To celebrate my birthday and Alfred's gotcha day, we're taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole! 

Alfred and I will be stepping it up from 10th–16th May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs by walking 140,000 steps (that's 20,000 steps a day, beating our usual 8,000ish by more than double!) 🐾🐾🐾

While Alf can't be registered as an official mental health assistance dog in the UK, he's certainly made a huge difference to my life, so I can only imagine the amazing impact guide dogs have on their blind and partially sighted handlers.

The sponsorship money you help us raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as a fully qualified guide dog. 

(PS, don't worry, Alf will be carried when necessary!!)

story: We're taking part in the sponsored walk that's good for the "sole" this May! As we walk we will be raising vital funds for Guide Dogs to help those with sight loss step out with confidence. The sponsorship money you help us raise really will make a difference. Just £140 could buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner, containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog, this includes the iconic white harness. Go on knock our socks off!

story:
We're taking part in the sponsored walk that's good for the "sole" this May! As we walk we will be raising vital funds for Guide Dogs to help those with sight loss step out with confidence. The sponsorship money you help us raise really will make a difference. Just £140 could buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner, containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog, this includes the iconic white harness. Go on knock our socks off!

Between the four of us, Team Ballard have set a target of walking 400,000 steps in a week at the end of May!

story:
We're taking part in the sponsored walk that's good for the "sole" this May! As we walk we will be raising vital funds for Guide Dogs to help those with sight loss step out with confidence. 

We are aiming for 100,000 steps in one week as a family to raise money for guide dogs. Libby and Hodie already have their very own guide dog Marley who they sponsor and would love to raise more money for Marley and all the other amazing dogs! 

 The sponsorship money you help us raise really will make a difference. Just £140 could buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner, containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog, this includes the iconic white harness. Go on knock our socks off!

Thanks in advance for all your well wishes and support……if you want to join us getting them steps in then more the merrier! Together we will do it! 

Love from Siobhan, Matt, Libby, Hodie and Lola x

story:
As part of my recovery from foot surgery, I'm taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole/soul!

It won’t seem like a lot to many, but I’m aiming to walk 8,000 steps a day for one week in May. This will be a milestone in my recovery. 

Nora (pictured) and I will be putting our best foot/paw forward to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs! 

The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. Go on - help me knock my socks off!

story:
I'm taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole! I will be stepping it up in my chosen week this May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs! The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. Go on - help me knock my socks off!

Im doing this also because I’m severely sight impaired so I know how difficult it is to be independent to get around safely even with just a cane. I think having a Guide Dog would help people like myself not only get around safely but would have an companion for life. The dogs become part of our life and they become a pet as well as a working dog, they need support from the Guide Dog teams to help us where we feel comfortable to be able to live independently.

story:
The sponsored walk thats good for the sole.

Your small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair designed by an international fashion icon!

How your funds will change lives...

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

story:
Guide Dogs are an amazing charity that give so much help and support to my incredible niece Izzy. 

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

How your funds will change lives...

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

story:
I am looking to raise money for Guide Dogs because a couple months ago my daughter Cheryl got her first guide dog, and I have seen first hand how much work goes into these amazing dogs. The process they go through and the cost of training the dogs then training the handler and even taking care of them is a lot. So we feel its just right we put our socks on and get our steps i and raise money to contribute back to what has changed her life. 

Even if its only a little it still means a lot to us.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I'm taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole! I will be stepping it up in my chosen week this May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs! 🦶 

I will be challenging myself to 115K steps in a week! It may not be a lot to some but suffering with numerous chronic health conditions myself such as Fibromyalgia, it’s going to be a push & no doubt end with many tears and a very, very long nap. :)!

I’ll be aiming for 15K steps on working days & 20K steps on my days off which is more than double my daily steps right now.! 😅 screenshots of my Daily steps will be added to my social media & updated on here too 🥰

The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. 

 Go on - help me knock my socks off! 🧦

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I am planning to do 10,000 steps a day between the 3rd and 9th May to help raise money for guide dogs. My target I would like to reach is £116 as this would buy a training kit for a guide dog. Any small amount would be greatly appreciated x

The sponsored walk thats good for the sole.Your small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair designed by an international fashion icon!How your funds will change lives...-£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.-£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training-£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.-£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: John Read
story:
The sponsored walk thats good for the sole.

Your small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair designed by an international fashion icon!

How your funds will change lives...

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

story: I have walked with my dogs all my life and recently got a new puppy. On these dog walks I have often talked with a neighbour who recently had a stroke and lost his sight. For a while he struggled to go out of his house and walk -  but a puppy, trained by the Guide dogs, entered his world and changed everything.  I know that every step of this sponsored walk will help people with sight loss take giant leaps of confidence. Just one week of me stepping out can make a huge difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. I hope to raise £ 1,000 which will help change their lives. £50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.-£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training-£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.-£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.
