pageSummaryWhat: This May I am walking as many steps as I can
pageSummaryWhy: they really are a life changing charity
image.caption: NA
media.images.image.caption: NA

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Nanny Jean
story:
Since we lost Nanny Jean last year Jacob has wanted to raise money for the guide dogs as she was blind. She never let this hold her back and we have other family members who have also had their sight effected. Which is why this is a cause so close to our hearts. 

Jacob already sponsors a dog called Marley, through his own pocket money each month but still feels like it isn’t enough...

...So me and Jacob are going to walk 210,000 steps between us within the the week commencing 3rd May. 

Jacob wants to raise as close to £1,000 as we can to help those that need it so throughout May we will try and find other ways to raise more.

Each of our small steps will help Guid Dogs to make giant leaps with the money we are going to raise. 

You might be asking how the money can change lives:

  • £50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements
  • £96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training
  • £116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs
  • £710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies

It’s thanks to all those that donate and fundraise that Guide Dogs can continue to provide life changing services. Please donate what you can it will all do some help!

story:
I started volunteering at guide dogs Atherton in 2018 helping out in the kennel blocks. This really opened my eyes as to how amazing these dogs are and the people behind them! The work they do is unreal! Every dog is cared for and trained to an unbelievable standard and they get lots of love and play time in between. Due to lockdown it has been impossible for me to help out as normal so this is my way of helping instead.

They really make a difference to peoples lives and it would mean the world if you could spare a small amount to help me reach my goal of £100.

I’ve chosen to do 100,000 steps on my chosen week with a toddler and baby in tow (I must be mad 🤪) if anything we will get a decent nights sleep with all the fresh air!

story:
Hey Everyone! 

I have decided to sign myself back to do the walk your socks off this year 10th May -16th May. Last year I had a target of 100,00 steps but walked 101,429 steps and that was during lockdown. 

My target is 100,000 steps again but hopefully I’ll do go over the target again this year. 

I’ve sponsored a guide dog named Monty for nearly 2 years. My Grandma Toots used to always take me to the guide dog stall at Moy & Scone game and that’s why I like to raise money for the charity. 

Did you know - Every hour, another person in the UK goes blind

180,000 people with sight loss rarely leave home alone

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss. By 2050, there could be nearly four million

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation. 

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. 

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society. 

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

eventName: Shane's First Marathon....with just 10 days training #26by30
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
So it seems there's no going back now! As you've found your way here, you'll already know I've made probably one of the craziest decisions of my life.

Why? Well, it's been a bit of a mad year for us all, and as much as it pains me to say, some of my only achievements in that time involve Netflix and Call of Duty. Thankfully I have a few more weeks to change that. 

3 days ago, in a moment of realisation that I will be turning 30 on the 1st of April, I decided it would be awesome to run my first Marathon. Yes, a whole 26.2 miles with no crowd to cheer me on, no medal waiting for me at the finish line and very little time to train. (For full disclosure - I run a couple of times a week, 10km being a solid Saturday. So certainly not starting from scratch!)

I'll be running from my home in East London to Hyde Park, with a few detours along the way. 26.2 miles / 42.2 km. 

While I'm embarking on this mad idea, I think it would be incredible to raise some money for a cause that's very close to my heart. Some of you may not know, but I spent a number of years being looked after by the incredible people at Great Ormond Street Hospital as a child. Not only have I come out of that period in my life stronger and healthier, but I also have some fond memories of a pretty rubbish time in my life.  

Every single day GOSH care for thousands of kids from all over the world. Some of whom will never see a 30th Birthday. This run will be for them. 

Age is just a number. 

So is 26.2. 

Wish me luck, I'm probably going to need it! 

Any donations/advice/tips will be massively appreciated and hopefully help me push me through the impending pain. 

Keep track of my progress here - https://www.instagram.com/shanewambeek/ 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
There is really so much to say about my grandmother, but as I write this all I can think about is the constant smile and happiness she bought to my face every time I was with her. With her I felt a sense of peace that only a grandmother can bring to their dear grandchild. I don't even know where to begin with her story. Lorna never gave up fighting, especially not in her last few months left on this earth. 

By donating towards the young fighters within Great Ormond Street we are making her proud and hopeful in saving as many lives as possible. Even though this is a page targeted to donate towards Great Ormond Street Hospital, my family and I just want to use ever resource we can to make my grandma's name something everyone we can reach remember. To say she was one of the most precious people in my life would be a total understatement. She was my everything. Thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. story:
Im Geeking out for GOSH and taking on a gaming challenge to raise money for the seriously ill children and their families at Great Ormond Street Hospital. They need us now, more than ever. 

For any parent, it is a worrying time when your child needs hospital treatment. But if your child is seriously ill, in the middle of a pandemic, this is even more daunting. 

With infection control restrictions on parents staying with their children, worry around travelling safely to and from hospital and being treated by staff in protective clothing, what is already a stressful time is even more challenging.

Your support could help fund services like the hospitals incredible Play team, Social Work Service and multi-faith chaplaincy team, as well as funding family accommodation so mums and dads stay near their children.

It'll also keep me going and give me the power-up I need to complete this challenge. Its quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the give now button on the right. Thanks!

With infection control restrictions on parents staying with their children, worry around travelling safely to and from hospital and being treated by staff in protective clothing, what is already a stressful time is even more challenging.

Your support could help fund services like the hospitals incredible Play team, Social Work Service and multi-faith chaplaincy team, as well as funding family accommodation so mums and dads stay near their children.

It'll also keep me going and give me the power-up I need to complete this challenge. Its quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the give now button on the right. Thanks!

story:
Fundraising for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity because of what they have done and continue to do for my daughter.

MiQers from around the globe are coming together for the 2021 MiQ Relay.

My challenge is to do a 100km bike ride.

Any contribution no matter how small is greatly appreciated 🙏

-----

MiQ RELAY 

What's this? - MiQers from around the globe pick a target run, walk, cycle, swim or ski - Either a time or distance. And over 1 weekend we all go out and try to complete our individual challenge all in the name of *GREAT CHARITIES* 

When is the big day? - 26th March (or over the weekend)

If you want to get involved there are 3 easy steps

*PICK YOUR CHALLENGE* This can be a walk, jog or cycle, whatever you want to commit to, push yourself and get training.

*SIGN UP* to the MiQ relay club and event on strava. Here - https://www.strava.com/clubs/MiQdigital

*RAISE SOME MONEY*, for the charity of the participants choice. Raising money for causes close to the hearts of MiQers (a fundraising page can only link to one charity so select 1 for your page)

Why? At the end, we will all celebrate the distance and the money raised by MiQers all over the world and in the virtual NEW NICK

We will tally the total distance too as landmarks for sign-ups and see how far we can when we UNITE

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Our beautiful little girl Poppy sadly passed away from 'AML Leukemia in down syndrome' quite rapidly, after relapsing in January 2020. She never gave up and was so brave and in her memory we would like to continue to help fight the battle and help to find a cure for this type of Leukemia. 

Scientists at GOSH are trialling a drug called mebendazole, a drug usually prescribed to treat parasitic worms, which has shown great promise in helping to stop this type of cancer spreading. 

Instead of flowers at Poppys funeral, we would like to ask for donations towards this research project with the aim of helping other children like Poppy.

Lots of love

Jo and Danny x

story:
Hi, thanks for visiting my JustGiving page! You're in the right place if you'd like to help families with children in need of special care and treatment. 

This year I've chosen to support GOSH Charity at the Lake District Challenge where I will trek 28 km (17.3 miles) on the 12th of June 2021. 

Now you might think, why GOSH Charity? Since October 2020 I've been employed by the Louis Dundas Centre at The Institute of Child Health as a Centre Administrator and got to find more about the need for awareness around this sector often ignored by the majority of the population. The centre conducts ground-breaking research in Palliative Care for children with life-limiting or life-threatening illnesses, by working closely with the clinical team at GOSH to make a tangible difference in the lives of these children and their families.

As for a bit of stats in the matter, as many as five children a day lose their lives to a rare disease, leaving their family scared for life, yet only 5% of UK research funding is spent on projects relating to child health. 

Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). GOSH sees more seriously ill children with rare diseases than any other UK hospital. The Charity has a unique opportunity to help GOSH transform the lives of these children, by funding research in key areas where they can make the greatest difference.

That said, thank you for taking the time to visit my page, every donation counts and I would highly appreciate your support to this worthy cause.

story:
With the help of Team Percipio (Jamie Taylor and Carly Ayre), I am aiming to raise money in aid of Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children.

In December 2020 Abi and I welcomed our second daughter, Holly, in to the world. Holly, was born with PHACES association, a spectrum disorder made up of a collection of different features. Most children with PHACES have a haemangioma (strawberry birthmark) and one other problem. In Holly’s case, she has a large haemangioma on her face and a narrow artery in her neck.

Great Ormond Street Hospital and Southend Hospital have both been great and given us all the support and treatment that Holly needs. With the treatment GOSH have given us, by the time Holly goes to school the birthmark should have almost disappeared. GOSH are specialists in diagnosing and treating rare and complex birthmarks and without their help Holly’s start in life could have been quite different.


Our Challenge

In July 2021 Team Percipio will start the Four Peak Challenge - walking the highest mountains in Scotland, England, North Wales and South Wales in 3 days.

The challenge will start in Scotland at Ben Nevis (1,344 metres) which is the tallest of the 4. We will then drive to the Lake District to climb Scafell Pike (978 metres) on day two and then to Wales to climb Snowdon (1,085 metres) and Pen Y Fan (886 metres) on day three.

Please support us in raising money for this amazing hospital.


Team Percipio

Stuart Byford

Jamie Taylor

Carly Ayre


Thank you!

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.


Great Ormond Street Hospital (then known as The Hospital for Sick Children) opened its doors at 49 Great Ormond Street on Valentine's Day 1852 with 10 beds.
It has since become one of the world’s leading children’s hospitals, housing the widest range of specialists under one roof.
Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) was founded by Dr Charles West, who was driven by the shockingly high level of infant mortality in the capital. It was the first hospital in the UK dedicated solely to the treatment of children.
Please help me to raise money for such a great cause.

story:
Great Ormond Street Hospital Childrens Charity (GOSH Charity) and McColls, the leading neighbourhood retailer, are delighted to announce a brand-new charity partnership that aims to raise £1million over the next three years.

Seriously ill children from across the UK travel to Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) for specialist treatment for rare and complex conditions.

The money raised by McColls will help fund GOSH Charitys vital parent accommodation service, supporting the refurbishment of 'McColl's House', which brings families closer together when a child is receiving treatment.

By partnering with GOSH Charity, McColls colleagues and customers will support families at the heart of their communities, right across the UK.

We are the world’s largest charity dedicated to saving lives through research.
Our vision is to bring forward the day when all cancers are cured.

Cancer Research UK is a registered charity in England and Wales (1089464), Scotland (SC041666), the Isle of Man (1103) and Jersey (247).
charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
On Friday 2nd July 2021 – Sunday 4th July 2021  Gwilym O’Donovan, Sean Higgins, Patrick Higgins, Dario Oliver, Kristian Hawkes, Tom James, Pat James, Joe Coughlin, Josh Cashman, Sam Byrne,
Josh Davidson, Rhys Hendley, Elliot Shotton, Sam Parselle, Brian Feeney, Josh Broom, Gary James  and myself will be attempting to canoe 85 miles down the River Wye.

Sean and James Austin will be joining us for part of the trip and Sam Bryne is sadly missing out this year due to injury.

Mark O’Donovan will be helping us out and dropping off supplies to us at different stages of the trip.  

The 85 mile route takes us from Glasbury – Redbrook and includes a section of rapids. We will camping overnight and aiming to do 24 miles in the first day, 26 miles on the second and 36 miles for the third day.

It’ll be a tough challenge but it’s something we are all desperate to complete. 

We will be raising money for Cancer Research. Its for a cause that is very important to us and you don’t need us to tell you that the stats and risk’s of Cancer are pretty shocking. All of our group know people close to us directly affected by Cancer. With Covid 19, the funding to Cancer Medical Services has taken a massive hit and is under resourced so we are hoping to raise as much as we can to help out.

So please help us get to our target and  donate what you can, no matter how big or small. Thanks a lot. 

Massive thanks to Josh at Celtic Canoes for all the advice and being so accommodating with supplying the canoes for the challenge. Anyone looking for a day out canoeing on the Wye, we couldn’t recommend these guys enough!

story:
My mum and I are committing to raising money for Cancer Research UK. Over lockdown, I've swapped my ice blades for roller blades, and have set myself the challenge of mastering off-ice skating. I'm aiming to skate faster with more confidence (once I've worked out how to stop, that is!) and perhaps learn a simple trick or two! 

I'd love to support a good cause in the process. So, my mum will be powerwalking alongside me as I do lap after lap of the village! Together, we'll cover 54 miles over 22 days - our respective ages! 

We'd love it if you could give a little to a Cancer Research to support the ongoing fight against cancer. Thank you so much!

story:
I am taking part in this years Ultra White Collar Boxing event for many reasons. I want to challenge and push myself to the limit, despite all of the negativity this year, to show myself that I can achieve positive things when I set my mind to it. I want to use this time to get fitter both physically and mentally, UWCB will give me the platform I need to start the year off right!

I want to raise money for charity, especially since this year has shown the generosity and  perseverance that most of these organisations have. They help make peoples lives better because it is the right thing to do.  Although there are so many amazing charities out there that do some much, I want to raise as many donations as possible for Cancer Research. Like many people, cancer has affected the lives of my loved ones around me, and because of that this charity is close to my heart. The incredible work that they do on a day to day basis is nothing short of a miracle.

Thank you for taking the time to read my story. If you feel like it, please donate, it is for a very worthy cause.

Mark x

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

It's scary to think about how many friends and family members have been affected by cancer. And it was scary to await the result of the growth that was removed from my own body in January 2020. Although I felt calm, I also felt like I was holding my breath for 6 months. Waiting for appointments. Waiting for surgery. Waiting for the result. Thankfully, I was in the clear, and in competent and caring hands all the way. 

More than ever, running has become my way of keeping myself as fit and healthy as I possibly can. And this year - also more than ever - it seemed important to give back in some small way. This is why I decided to take on this 'bonkers' challenge of running a 100km trail race in one day and fundraise for Cancer Research UK and support their efforts to save more lives.

The training is well under way and most weekends you will find me roaming the Surrey Hill trails. With restrictions easing it's looking more and more likely that the event will take place as scheduled on the 10th. July 2021.

story:
1 in 2 of us will get cancer. 

My Mum died of cancer in 2020 & a year on my Dad has been diagnosed with kidney cancer. 

Treatments are constantly improving & I want to help this process by raising money for a charity that is dedicated to this life changing research. 

I’m also very aware that the only way I can reduce my own chance of getting cancer is by eating a healthy diet & taking regular exercise. 

Please consider donating (or taking part!) to this worthwhile cause.

charity.description:
We are the world’s largest charity dedicated to saving lives through research.
Our vision is to bring forward the day when all cancers are cured.

Cancer Research UK is a registered charity in England and Wales (1089464), Scotland (SC041666), the Isle of Man (1103) and Jersey (247).
charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Earlier this year, I was diagnosed with stage 4 breast cancer, which has spread to my liver and spine. Research has enabled doctors to develop a greater understanding of cancers and I have started treatment, which I will be on until a cure is found. Apart from being more tired than usual and a lowered immune system, the treatment is going very well.

Cancer Research UK is one of the leading organisations doing amazing work and clinical trials and hopefully a cure can be found soon.

I am walking 100k up and down the Jurassic Coast in May. It is a big challenge as the hills are very steep!

Then in June, I take on a weekend of challenges, swimming 5k on the Friday in Lake Windermere and then a SwimRun on the Saturday. These two challenges will be particularly hard, as Covid has seen the pools closed so training won't start until they reopen in mid April.

Please donate if you're able, as their work is essential in preventing, treating and hopefully curing cancer.

eventName: In Memory Donation Page for North Wales
owner: Marie Curie North Wales In Memory Donation Page
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The Marie Curie Nursing Service in North Wales is here to provide hands on care and support to people, and their families who are living with terminal illness. 

Marie Curie deliver one to one care and comfort to people who are
experiencing end of life.  This planned service is always provided in the
comfort and safety of the persons own home, with a single nurse, assigned to a single patient, for a full 9 hour shift that starts at 10pm in the evening, until 7am the following morning. 

This one to one care supports the family and carers to rest in the
knowledge that their loved one is in safe, competent, and compassionate hands. 

Marie Curie also provides an emergency 'Rapid Response' service that is run from Ysbyty Glan Clwyd and Wrexham Maelor's out of hours emergency department. Our nurses work in teams of 2 to respond at short notice to emergency call outs. This vital service helps prevent unnecessary hospital admissions, allowing the patient to remain in the comfort of their own home. 

Living through the loss of a loved one affects everybody differently. Marie Curie is here to offer support on life, dying and bereavement to anybody who needs us. More information can be obtained here Information and support (mariecurie.org.uk).

One way to celebrate the life of somebody important to you is to make an in-memory donation to a charity that has supported them or was close to their heart. 

We're incredibly grateful to everyone who considers supporting us in
this special way, at what may be a difficult time.

If you would like to talk about how you're finding things, our Support
Line is there to listen and can be contacted on 0800 090 2309.

The coronavirus pandemic is having an impact on funerals, which can be upsetting and difficult for everyone involved. For practical information about attending a funeral, ideas for remembering a loved one, and supporting your family and friends when you can't be there in person, please visit our page about funerals and Coronavirus.

If you are able to and would like to donate to this very worthy cause and help someone in need, I’d be so very grateful. 🙌🏼 As the saying goes, every little helps!

story:
We wanted to honour our beautiful mums memory by giving something back and showing our appreciation and gratitude to Marie Curie for the care and support they gave to our mum throughout the last months of her brave battle with ovarian cancer.

Our mum Diane was a loving wife, mum to 3 daughters, nan to 8 grandchildren and a friend to many., she passed on 14th January 2021 having just turned 62 on new years day, after her fight against ovarian cancer she had been diagnosed with at stage 4 only 18 months before. She fought so hard to stay and we are all still trying to come to terms with it, as the loss for us as a family is just immense. 

You hear of this horrendous disease all the time, but experiencing first hand and witnessing the suffering it causes, it really makes you realise just how special the staff from Marie Curie are in all they do, caring and supporting those that are sadly terminally ill. 

#EarthAngels 

I know she would want us to say thank you in some way, and this is a start.

We will love and miss her, always xxx

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Graham Forrester
story:
The Marie Curie Glasgow Hospice supports people living with a terminal illness and those closest to them to live as well as possible.

The Hospice is often very different from what people expect  it is a warm, friendly space with beautiful gardens, delicious home-cooked food and personalised care. Every person is treated as an individual and helped to reach their goals and fulfil their wishes. A team of nurses, doctors, social workers, physiotherapists, chaplains, bereavement counsellors and pharmacists work together, putting every person at the centre of their care.

Throughout Covid-19 Glasgow Hospice teams have been working around the clock to continue supporting local people. Death, dying and bereavement is at the forefront of peoples minds and Marie Curie knows what a difference the right care at the end of life can make.

They cant do any of this without your support. Thank you for your generous donation which supports the Glasgow Hospice and Marie Curie across the UK.

Rain or shine, we’re going on an adventure! I’ve teamed up with @mariecurieuk & @ntu3peaksteam to embark on the “Three Peaks Challenge” in June, a journey to the 3 highest peaks in the UK; Ben Nevis in Scotland (1,345 m), Scafell Pike in England (978 m), and Snowdonia (1,085 m) in Wales in around 36 hours. A total estimated distance of 42 KM & a total ascent of 3,000 m. Just typing this got me huffing & puffing!

That said, I am fundraising in support of @mariecurieuk; a chairty with origins that date back to the late 40s, which provides care and support to the terminally ill.

Every non-anonymous donor will receive a collection of postcards called the “NOTTS Collection”; a one off series of postcards with photos captured in #Nottingham.

Thank you, I appreciate your support!

story:
On 23 March it’ll be one year since the first UK lockdown. Since then, millions of people have been bereaved, both as a result of covid-19 and due to other causes.

The restrictions we’ve all been living under have meant that many of us – including children and young people – have had to grieve without the comfort of having friends and family around them. The National Day of Reflection will give us a time to unite and reflect on this tragic loss of life and our collective grief as a nation.

Join the minute’s silence at 12 noon on 23 March to show your support for the millions of people who’ve been bereaved and take a moment to connect with someone you know who’s grieving. 

Have a chat, send a card, a message or spring flowers.

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last.
We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how.
Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

My challenges start with a virtual Winter Walk on 27th March and will (hopefully!) finish with climbing Kilimanjaro in October with lots more challenges in between.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Jennifer Clements
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

On Mothers Day, 22nd March 2009 our world fell apart when we lost our amazing Mam to cancer. Time is a healer apparently, but it never really gets easier. I find myself thinking about her often, and sometimes those memories are so special thinking about all the fun times. Then there's the ones that make you feel like you've been slapped in the face and you actually cannot believe life can be so cruel. 12 years without her in our lives and I've decided I want to do something in her memory. I want to raise money for Marie Curie Newcastle so that others can be supported and looked after like Mam was. She wasn't at Marie Curie for long, but I still remember the care she received when she was so ill.

SO I have decided to get my long mop cut off. Not shaved as my Sis will kill me for being a bald bridesmaid, but a very short style. It's taken me 4 years to get my hair this length, so it's a big step for me. If you are able to support and sponsor me it would be very much appreciated. I will also be donating my actual hair to the Little Princess Trust.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: June Chatterton
story:
In 2010 my mum was diagnosed with a Grade 4 Brain Tumour.  After a short illness, in October 2010 at the age of 58 she sadly passed away.

Those of you that know me, know that not only was she my mum, but she was my best friend.  Many people experience the effects of cancer in their lifetime, and my mum was no exception, losing her own mum to cancer when she was only 15.  

At the start of 2020 I decided to mark the 10 year anniversary of her death by running the Royal Parks Half marathon in London and to raise money for one of her favourite charities, Marie Curie.  The event was to take place in October 2020 but sadly was postponed to April 2021 and has again been postponed to October 2021.  

The April 2021 event is now taking place as a virtual event and having committed to raising money in memory of my mum I have decided to run the half mararthon distance on 11 April 2021, by taking part in the virtual event that is taking place instead of the actual race, although I will still be takin part in the actual event in October.

So on 11 April 2021, with the support of my amazing friend and running buddy, Rebecca Walker I will be running the stretch of the Transpennine Trail, between Pensitone and Kirkburton in the hope of raising as much money as I can.   Every £1 helps.

Thank you 

Michelle xxxx

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
In Wales, the RNLI has been operating at full capacity since the start of lockdown. Our service has been rescuing people throughout the Coronavirus pandemic and our heroic crews commitment to saving lives at sea has not stopped. Unfortunately, our ability to raise funds through traditional methods has been limited.

The average lifeboat station in Wales costs £155,000 to run and we are going to have a significant shortfall in income this year due to the Coronavirus. We are asking all our friends and communities to donate what they can to keep us running.

From Flint around the coast to Penarth, we will always be there to keep you and your loved ones safe, on our watch, there will be no preventable deaths on Welsh coasts. Please help us fulfil that mission.

For ideas on how to support or get involved please contact nick_evans@rnli.org.uk

Your donation to this page will help support the running of stations in the Wales as follows:
Aberdovey, Abersoch, Aberystwyth, Angle, Barmouth, Barry Dock, Beaumaris, Borth, Burry Port, Cardigan, Conwy, Criccieth, Fishguard, Flint, Holyhead, Horton and Port Eynon, Little and Broad Haven, Llandudno, Moelfre, New Quay, Penarth, Port Talbot, Porthcawl, Porthdinllaen, Pwllheli, Rhyl, St Davids, Tenby, The Mumbles and Trearddur Bay.

Yng Nghymru, mae’r RNLI wedi bod yn gweithredu ar gapasiti llawn ers dechrau’r cyfnod clo. Trwy gydol pandemig y coronafeirws, mae criwiau arwrol yr RNLI wedi ymrwymo i wasanaethu'r cyhoedd trwy achub bywydau ar y mr. Er hyn, mae ein gallu i gasglu arian trwy ddulliau traddodiadol wedi bod yn gyfyngedig.

Ar gyfartaledd, mae cost o £155,000 ynglwm g ariannu un gorsaf bad achub yng Nghymru ond rydym yn rhagweld diffygion sylweddol yn yr incwm eleni o ganlyniad i’r coronafeirws. Felly rydym yn gofyn yn garedig i gyfeillion a chymunedau yr RNLI am gyfraniadau er mwyn sicrhau bod gorsafoedd yn gallu parhau yn weithredol.

Ar hyd yr arfordir o Fflint i Fro Morgannwg, byddwn wrth law er mwyn eich cadw chi a’ch anwyliaid yn ddiogel.Ein amcan yw sicrhau nad oes marwolaethau y gallwn eu hatal yn digwydd ar arfordiroedd Cymru.

story:
Thank you for supporting this fundraising page for this year Pedal for Appledore RNLI Challenge.

Appledore RNLI are fielding their own crew team to join the ‘Pedal for Appledore RNLI’

Appledore Lifeboat crew have put together their own crew team to join in the ‘Pedal for Appledore RNLI’ Sponsored Cycling Challenge, the latest fundraising scheme set up by the Appledore RNLI Guild.

‘Pedal for Appledore RNLI’ provides a COVID friendly method of fundraising for the RNLI whose funds have been severely hit over the last year. The work of the RNLI and its volunteers has continued 24/7 throughout the pandemic, yet many of the normal, ever popular methods of raising funds to pay for this charitable work, have not been possible.

In addition to most of them working full time, family life, lifeboat training and shouts, the volunteer crew of Appledore RNLI have put a team together to raise money to go towards the operating costs of running their own boats and station.  They aim to ride between 500 – 1000 miles in the ‘Pedal for Appledore RNLI’ cycling challenge which will take place between 2 to 30 April 2021.

eventName: In memory of Colin Wylie Robertson
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Colin Wylie Robertson
story:
Colin Wylie Robertson died on 15th March 2021, one day before his 96th birthday. We will be remembering him at a family gathering on 9th April 2021.

He loved the sea, especially at Beer in Devon where he spent happy times as a child with his family on holiday. He always remembered the fishing boats and fishermen there with great fondness. He also lived for some time in Saltburn-on -Sea where he would fish and muck about in boats.

He and Miranda honeymooned in Mousehole, Cornwall and when we children were young we holidayed in Devon or Cornwall. Colin would swim in the sea and go fishing or out in a boat whenever there was an opportunity.

We would be delighted if we are able to raise some money in his memory for his favourite charity.

Thank you so much.

Amanda, Davina and Quentin.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The RNLI has answered Mayday calls for nearly 200 years, from those called from sinking fishing boats, to families swimming on busy beaches, to dog walkers cut-off by the tide. It's the most urgent plea, used by mariners when life is in immediate danger and when their lifesavers hear those words they launch courageously into the unknown to help those who rely on their help.

This May, as summer approaches, they're the ones sending out a Mayday call. As we look forward to 2021 and beyond, they know that they'll be facing the busiest summer season for the lifesavers to come. And to keep them safe, ready and knowing they can handle whatever the summer brings, they need our help.

They're counting on us to answer their call and take on the Mayday Mile. Our support will help the crew stand strong as our busiest summer season approaches.

story:
As a rower, I understand how important it is to respect the water and the risks it creates.  Living by the sea means that I also hugely appreciate the guardianship of our local beach lifeguards and the local lifeboat crews who are always on-call for emergencies.  Very soon, I'll be able to spend less time on my rowing machine and enjoy rowing on real water again - I want to do something practical to support our lifesavers before I go back out there.

As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

Our RNLI lifeboats in Northern Ireland protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Northern Irelands unrivalled coasts and inland waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need the help of the RNLI and we will always be there to answer that call.

story:
Senior School pupil, Theo Wade, is supporting the newly launched RNLI appeal to raise £78,000 for the new D class inshore lifeboat which will, once again, be named in memory of his cousin, Ollie Naismith. 

In 2010 the D-Class Inshore Lifeboat Ollie Naismith was officially named and went on service at Looe. The lifeboat was named after a popular local teenager Ollie Naismith who sadly died in a tragic road traffic accident in 2009. Ollies parents, Maxine and John Naismith spearheaded a fundraising campaign to raise the funds for the lifeboat which has gone on to save many lives in and around Looe including the life of Louis Webber, a young local lad who was of a similar age to Ollie. The lifeboat is now coming to the end of its operational life so the team at Looe Lifeboat station are teaming up with the Naismiths and Webber family to launch the Looe Lifeboat Appeal to raise the £78,000 required to provide a replacement lifeboat which will be named the Ollie Naismith II.Your donation to this community appeal will help to fund this lifeboat which will continue the selfless work of our volunteer lifeboat crew in Looe.

story:
To raise awareness for the RNLI, safety at sea and hopefully a small donation. We are keen sailors and our mum was part of the Burnham-on-Crouch RNLI for years and so this is an important cause for us. Additionally, this is the year of the great British summer holiday with more and more people enjoying the sea and British waterways. The RNLI are sea safety experts - and so can provide  information to help you stay safe on the beaches, exploring the coast and on the water: https://rnli.org/safety

So tasking ourselves with walking 100,000 steps (the aim, with caveat that even if we don't complete this target - all money raised will go to the RNLI), we will be walking from Burnham-on-Crouch and looping around the Dengie peninsula. Some of the money raised will hopefully go directly to the Burnham-on-Crouch RNLI station. 

From the RNLI: Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

As my life long best friend and my rock it seems only fitting to try and fulfil one of his wishes.

Sleep tight my darling. X xx X

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As you all know I lost my beloved Stephen on the 27th of January to his heart anyrisum rupturing.

As you can all imagine we're all heart broken . Due to covid19 we couldn't have all the people there he /we would have wanted .ste/nobby would have wanted a donation box for the RNLI.

so we have decided to set this page up.

as you  all may know ste always went down  to Cornwall where he loved to go one holiday. 

Every year he would saved his loose change in a big jar and he would take it down to looe or St ives and put it into the RNLI donation box. This is something he's done over the last 20 years. 

 So please even if its a £1 lets get to his target. 

you never know when your on your holiday whether you would need them . 

thanks so much for reading my story

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Chris Williams
story:
On 12th March 2021, we sadly lost our beloved husband, father, grandfather, brother, uncle and friend, Chris. 

Chris' cremation has been arranged for 31st March at Reading Crematorium and we know there are people who will be unable to attend the funeral due to the current pandemic. We have set this up for those that would like to make a donation to charity in Chris' memory. 

From a young age, Chris loved to fish by the sea. Nothing made him happier than sitting on a beach with a lager watching his float bob up and down listening to the roar of the sea. He had a great respect for the RNLI - the people who saved the lives of his fellow fishermen - and it was his favourite charity to donate to. 

Chris would have wanted us all to raise a glass for him in a pub somewhere and we hope that we will be able to do that with everyone soon.
title: In Memory of Chris Williams

story:
If you had told me this time last year that I’d be able to run a 10K or that I would even enjoy running I would’ve laughed! Like many I have spent my lockdown getting into my fitness and running has become a regular part of my life! This will be my first ever official 10K sponsored run and what better charity to raise money for than RNLI. More information below: 

This year Lymington RNLI Lifeboat Station is holding its 20th annual 10k and kids fun run. Due to the ongoing situation with Covid-19, this years event will be their first virtual event!This is the biggest fundraiser in the Lymington RNLI calendar, with the event usually supported and run by our fantastic station and branch volunteers, with funding coming wholly from public donations. Thank you for helping raise vital funds for RNLI Lymington Station. With every pound donated, you'll be supporting our lifesaving work, which for over 50 years has provided a lifesaving service in the western Solent, Needles Channel and eastern sector of Christchurch Bay

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
My task:
With more and more people having staycations this year, myself included, there is likely to be a higher demand on the RNLI as a result.

My task is to ride 207 miles, with just under 10,000ft of ascent, from Mudeford Lifeboat Station to Weston-Super-Mare Lifeboat Station, stop for some fuel and then ride back to Mudeford LS.

The reason for the choice is that it marks the first two stations in the South West region on both South and North coasts. As I live in this region, I felt it was a good route to take.

I have shared my Strava account, so that you will be able to see my rides. Some will be long, in preparation for the big day and some will be shorter, but a case of keeping the legs spinning.

I will also be doing some off the bike training to assist my efforts on the bike.

Please also feel free to follow me on Facebook, where I will also be posting some updates and photo's as I prepare for the ride.

I will be setting out early on (DATE BEING CONFIRMED) and fundraising will remain open until 26th July 2021.

A little extra about the RNLI:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.


Thank you.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The first lifeboat station was established in the beautiful seaside village of Courtmacshery in 1825, one of the first to be founded in Ireland. Its crews have been presented with 14 awards for gallantry. 

The lifeboat is very central to the life of Courtmacsherry and is very much part of the proud history and tradition of this beautiful seaside village. The station's current lifeboat is the "Frederick Storey Cockburn" - a "Trent" class lifeboat. This class of lifeboat was designed to lie afloat at a deep water mooring or at a berth. At Courtmacsherry the lifeboat lies approximately 100 yards offshore from the lifeboat station and is accessed by a small boarding boat.

Our RNLI lifeboats in Ireland protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. Irelands unrivalled coasts and inland waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

eventName: Croydon Branch Step challenge for Tower Appeal
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Members of the RNLI Croydon fundraising Branch are taking on a step challenge this May to support the RNLI Thames Appeal. Taking on as many laps of Bingham Park as possible in 3 hours, Stephen hopes to raise as much as possible to support the new lifeboat station build at Tower on the River Thames. Look out for us on 3rd May in wellies as he takes on his challenge for Tower!

Every pound and penny raised on this fundraising page will go towards building the new lifeboat station. The current station is old, cramped and no longer fit for purpose. It lacks proper facilities, and the structure is beyond economical repair, and there is no privacy for vulnerable casualties. 

We urgently need your help to fund this purpose-built lifeboat station at Tower to carry on our lifesaving mission. We don't receive government funding so are really counting on your support to help meet the £5M total cost of this project. This is a once-in-a-generation opportunity. Its a chance for you to be part of an enduring London landmark something really special. 

You'll be part of the RNLI crew and your donation will help save lives in the capital for decades to come. 

Thank you for your support

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The RNLI has answered mayday calls for nearly 200 years, from those called from sinking fishing boats, to families swimming on busy beaches, to dog walkers cut off by the tide. It's the most urgent plea, used by mariners when life is in immediate danger and when their lifesavers hear those words they launch courageously into the unknown to help those who rely on their help.

This May, as summer approaches, they're the ones sending out a mayday call. As we look forward to 2021 and beyond, they know that they'll be facing the busiest summer season for the lifesavers to come. And to keep them safe, ready and knowing they can handle whatever the summer brings, they need our help.

They're counting on us to answer their call and take on the Mayday Mile. Our support will help the crew stand strong as our busiest summer season approaches.

eventName: Dublin Bay Running Club Virtual 5 mile Race
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
This fundraiser is very important to us at Howth Lifeboat.  The past year has been tough in so many ways but, like you, we made sacrifices and we made it through.

Although we’re still struggling through the pandemic, there’s
promise of a better spring. The sky is a little lighter, the grass a little
greener. With longer days on the way, more people will be drawn to the water.
Hope of rescue is what they’ll need should they find themselves in trouble. Can we count on you to make sure we’re there for them?

When coronavirus struck, it impacted our fundraising – and we’re
still feeling the effects. We had to cut back. Training courses were cancelled.
Planned lifeboat maintenance was delayed. But still the calls for help kept coming. Wear and tear on kit and equipment carried on. 

Will you keep us ready for when we’re needed most?

Thank you for your support.

Howth Lifeboat Crew

story:
“So, here we are … again …

Some of you might have noticed that I’ve not been doing all that much cycling recently … around about six years of recently. It also appears that I’m not as aerodynamic as a result!

I have decided to challenge myself to achieve the mighty sum of 50 miles around Norfolk on my old trusty pedal bike. I thought it might be nice to support a charity along the way. Fitness wise - I’m starting from nothing but I’m going to give it everything!

I’ve picked the RNLI as my charity of choice due to the lifelong family links I’ve got with the Sheringham Station. I’m also very aware that once the Covid restrictions become a distant memory, many families will head to the coast for a well deserved family break - I fear that they might not be as well rehearsed with sea safety as they need to be.”

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

eventName: Harry and Thomas’s two day trek for WWF
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Our names are Harry and Thomas and while on a walk we started talking about endangered and extinct animals. We then decided that we want to help stop animals going extinct so we asked our mummies how we could help. We thought the best man to ask how we could help would be Sir David Attenborough So we set out writing him a letter. After a week of waiting David Attenborough replied to our letter (I know amazing). He said that we should contact the WWF if we are interested in wildlife conservation and that’s what we did. So here we are now trying raise much needed funds to help the worlds wildlife. 

How we are going to do this... Well we are going to walk to the top of Bosley Cloud, Teggs Nose, Shutlinsloe and White Nancy all in two days. 

So please help us by donating a little or a lot, we won’t mind 😉 Please read on for more information about the WWF. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

story: Millions of people across the world will be switching off their lights for an hour from 8.30pm on Saturday 27th March to celebrate Earth Hour. Join me by donating to my fundraising event to support WWF this Earth Hour. We're destroying forests, choking the oceans with plastic, decimating wildlife population sizes, and causing devastating changes to the climate. We are the first generation to know we are destroying the world. And we could be the last that can do anything about it. That's why Earth Hour is so vital. It gives a powerful voice to people everywhere who want to put the world on the path to recovery. Thank you.

eventName: Beth and Isla's Sponsored Litter Pick
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hello we are Beth and Isla and we care a lot about our planet, to help we decided to do a sponsored litter pick where all the money goes to the charity WWF. 

For every bag of litter we collect, you can sponsor us and all the money that we receive goes to the charity WWF. This is an international organization founded in 1961 that works in the field of wilderness preservation and the reduction of human impact on the environment. Every year, 9 BILLION tons of litter ends up in our ocean which is more than what is produced (250 million tons) Every 60 seconds, the equivalent of a truckload of plastic enters the ocean. 

In 2015, National Geographic reported that there are 5.25 trillion pieces of plastic litter in the ocean and The Washington Post projects that by 2050 the metric tons of the plastic will outweigh the metric tons of fish living in our oceans, if the current rates of plastic dumping continue Although these two statistics are extremely overwhelming, scientists and researchers are more interested in what types of rubbish that are most common in our oceans. 

Facts About Plastic Pollution 

1. About 8.3 billion tonnes of plastic has been produced since the 1950s – the weight of roughly a billion elephants or 47 million blue whales. 2. There are five trillion pieces of plastic in our oceans – enough to circle the Earth over 400 times. 

3. Only about 9% of this plastic has been recycled, 12% has been burned and the remaining 79% has ended up in landfills or the environment.

How to help! 

Instead of throwing away that plastic bottle, recycle it! It could be used again and again for other uses such as new plastic bottles!Go litter picking! 

Purchase items secondhand 

Cut back on snacks, make your own! 

Trying growing your own food 

Buy reusable water bottles that you can refill when you need to (best buy mettle ones!) 

Get the best from single use bags 

Spread the word! 

How long does it take to biodegrade? 

A single plastic bag takes 1000 years to biodegrade 

A plastic nappy takes about 250 

years to biodegrade 

Batteries take 100 years to 

biodegrade 

Plastic bottles take 450 years 

to biodegrade

story:
About me and this art work

My name is Denisa and I am currently in my first year studying BA fine art mixed media at the university of Westminster in London. 

About 6 years ago I created an artwork that was supposed to promote animal awareness. I have created the above rhino print as one of these works. 
This work is created using a technique of heat press which means that when painting is exposed to high temperature the paint will imprint itself onto fabric. However every time it is exposed to the heat, less pigment gets transferred. This effect makes the rhino disappears.

This photograph is combination of 20 separate prints on fabric that have been scanned and collaged together. 
Photograph is numbered 1 out of 1 
Size - 37x30cm 

How to win the print
Every £1 counts as an entry to the draw to win this print. You have to put down your name. There is option to tick to share info with me but hide from public.
Donations are accepted until the 22nd of April (Earth Day)
Draw will be held on the 23nd of April and the draw will be held live on my instagram account @denisaarts

About the charity

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

story:
Hey everyone, this is Seb!

Those who know me are well aware that I am not one for running. I joined London Landmarks Half Marathon, rather spontaneously, to get myself out of my comfort zone and push my limits (being able to do it for a good cause gave me that extra push!).

Growing up in Costa Rica has enabled me to develop a unique connection with nature, and, having lived in London over a year now made me appreciate that connection even more. Being close with nature has helped see with clear eyes what the natural world is currently facing. We only have one planet and, unfortunately, we are not living in harmony with it.

When it came to decide for what charity I should run for, I found myself in the unique position to help solve one ‘global issue’ across different areas. I chose to support WWF because they are at the heart of the global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to ‘exploit’ only their fair share of natural resources.

For those who enjoy a walk in the park, swimming in clean waters, picking fresh fruits and looking at the stars in a clear sky, I am doing this for you. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Your support is much appreciated.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

I love everything art, but I also care about the environment! I really wanted to help, so I came up with this. I am creating E-cards (Electronic Cards) for people like you to get whenever you donate to my charity, Cool Earth. So far, there are 10 designs to choose from, ranging from Happy Birthday to Get Well Soon and Easter cards! Your card will be in a video format, with music, card design and personal message. Thank you for supporting me, but most importantly Cool Earth and our planet!

WHAT TO DO:

1. Look through the gallery at the top of the page and decide which design you would like. If you would like another at any given time, you must do this in a separate donation (one request per donation).

2. Donate! This can be any amount - all donations will go to Cool Earth.

3. Once you have donated, check your emails for a receipt from JustGiving. A message will be there with an email address to send your request to, if you wish to receive an e-card.

4. In the email, please state clearly: your chosen card design (refer to this using the caption underneath it in the gallery), your message (inside the card), and a name or age (number) for any of the 5 personalised cards (labelled as "(personalised)" in their caption). Here is an example...

Card: Happy Birthday Toucan     Message: To Zoey, Happy Birthday! Enjoy your day. Love from, Eve.

For the "Subject Line" of the email, you should write "Cool Earth Card".

5. You will receive your e-card within 48 hours of sending your request. If your request isn't clear enough, an email will be sent as a reply asking any questions needed. Please note that any copyright will be removed during the process of making your card.

story:
“No”

“Absolutely not”

“Doubt it”

“Lol nah”

“Have you lost your mind?”


Just a selection of the answers The Chief Ninja - Hayley Field received when she asked her Ninja apprentices if they wanted to walk 100km in 30 hours with no sleep.


Yet, for reasons best known to someone else, we all ended up saying

“Yes”


So here we are.


7 (apparently persuadable) people, plus our persistent leader, preparing to walk across the South Downs between 24th & 26th of September.


It’s gonna be a right laugh.


Said absolutely no one.


But, it will be an opportunity to raise some much needed funds for Oxfam and the great work they do at home and abroad in alleviating poverty.


So that, dear reader is why you’re reading this.


Because, lets not mess about, if we’re gonna end up blistered,  miserable and wondering why the hell we’re climbing hills in West Sussex in the middle of the night, we’re gonna need some support.


Yeah, you could come down with an air horn and cheer us on.



OR


Better still, you could sponsor us…


...Even if it's just a few quid.


As the great philosopher Tesco once said:


“Every Little Helps”


And in return, we’ll be forever grateful, and keep you updated on our training and progress with photos and social media posts and stuff.


If you don’t sponsor us?


We’ll keep you updated on our progress with EVEN MORE photos and social media posts and stuff.


Go on, you know you want to...



Trailwalker UK supports the incredible work of both Oxfam Great Britain and The Gurkha Welfare Trust.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Trailwalker is challenging team endurance event, either walk, job or run 100km non-stop across the South Downs in under 30 hours. In teams of four with a support team crew to help to get you across the finish line.  

Trailwalker UK supports the incredible work of both Oxfam Great Britain and The Gurkha Welfare Trust.

The Gurkhas are soldiers from Nepal who are recruited into the British Army and have been for over 200 years. They are renowned for their loyalty, professionalism and bravery. We ensure that Gurkha veterans, their widows and their wider communities are able to live with dignity in their home-country of Nepal.

The Gurkha Welfare trust delivers  packages of care to Gurkha veterans and widows to ensure they can live with dignity. Our Pensioner Support Teams journey into the hills of Nepal on motorbikes, in 4×4 vehicles and on-foot to pay them a pension, check their health and deliver medication in their own homes. We’re also there in times of need, be it floods, fire damage or earthquakes, providing extra support to help these brave men and women get back on their feet.

The trust provide an international standard of medical care for all Gurkha veterans and their families living in Nepal. We give this at our state-of-the-art Medical Clinics, at Medical Camps, during home visits by specialist staff and arranging subsidised treatments at carefully selected national hospitals.

Oxfam is  the world’s leading experts in providing clean water in emergency situations. That means, 24/7, 365 days a year, we’re ready to supply, deliver, build and maintain life-saving drinking water supplies and toilets for thousands of people – in the places no one else can reach. 

Supplying Solar-powered water pumps. Local radio shows on new farming techniques. Supporting women and girls to learn, earn and lead. From the practical to the culture-changing, we’re helping people to find new ways to build fair, independent lives for themselves – and to spread these ideas far and wide.

This is not about charity. It’s about justice. Oxfam  stands up and speaks out against the causes of poverty – challenging the traditions that hold women back, demanding fairness where there’s inequality, defending the rights of refugees. From grassroots projects to global campaigning, we push decision-makers to break down the barriers that keep people poor, so that every person on the planet can leave poverty behind forever.

story: Saxmundham Surgery proved to be comfortably the most successful Surgery in the Country in giving the first round of vaccines to over 50's and 16 to 50 year olds with underlying conditions. 66% of all adults in Saxmundham have received their first dose. The Patient Participation Group (PPG) at the Surgery felt they would like to organise a public display of gratitude to the Surgery. Dr Havard  suggested supporting the UNICEF COVAX fund which is working hard to see that no country is left behind with regard to vaccinating its' people. story:
Covid-19 is the biggest global crisis since World War Two. And children won’t be safe until everyone they rely on is safe.


Central and West Warrington Primary Care Network has so far delivered 20,000 to the people of Warrington. 

By supporting our pay it forward appeal you can ensure that those with less developed healthcare systems have the same opportunity.

With your support, Unicef will help deliver 2 billion Covid-19 vaccines for health workers and the most high risk people on our planet.

From buying and transporting supplies through to administering the vaccine, you’ll help deliver history. Your donation will ensure:

  • vaccines get to even the most remote places in the world
  • vaccines are safely stored using cold chain equipment
  • health workers are protected and trained to vaccinate their communities

Donate now and help protect health workers in low- and middle-income countries. Your gift of £45 could transport 1593 doses of vaccines.

Donate now: Help deliver vaccines, tests and treatment to protect health workers and people at high risk.

eventName: Walking for the children of Yemen
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I aim to walk 10 miles a day for 7 days between Sunday 28 March and 4 April - come rain or shine - to support Unicef's work on the ground in Yemen, which is suffering the largest humanitarian crisis in the world.  More than 12 million children in Yemen are in danger from war, disease and hunger.  Many of the diseases and infections should be easily preventable, but half of the health facilities are no longer functioning after 6 years of conflict.

Your donation could help provide water, sanitation, hygiene and nutrition for the 1.71 million internally displaced children who are not only facing the challenges of this on-going conflict, but also having to deal with Covid.

In spite of the cover photo, all of this walk will be local to home - a more gently undulating and easier landscape to navigate.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page and a massive "thank you" to everyone who has donated so far and enabled me to reach and pass my target.  

I'm still training at the moment.  The proper ten mile a day walk starts on Sunday, 29 March.  I hope the weather will be reasonably kind, but whatever it holds I'll be out there knowing so many people are supporting me.

Donating to JustGiving is very easy.   If you are able to use Gift Aid that will add another 25% to your donation.  Once you donate, JustGiving will send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Thank you.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Yemen is facing a major humanitarian crisis. A devastating conflict has left children and families in urgent need of food, water and medical supplies. Currently, 1.71 million children are internally displaced. UNICEF is concerned that the spread of coronavirus in Yemen is likely to be devastating. Only one in three people have access to running water, very few people have soap, and many healthcare facilities are closed or only able to provide a very basic service. Any outbreak will place even greater demands on medical staff and already scarce hospital resources such as gloves, soap and ventilators. 

For more information on the Yemen crisis and what UNICEF is doing to help, please take a look at their website: https://www.unicef.org/emergencies/yemen-crisis

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: We are fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems. We believe that not only people living in wealthy countries deserve health care, especially during a pandemic and we should do our best to make a difference and help people that might be struggling. So please if you have anything to spare please donate because even a small amount will make a huge difference. Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers.The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak and will continue to do so with help from donations. All donations  made to our page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

OUR CHOICE TO SUPPORT UNICEF’S PRIORITY INITIATIVES:

Health and Nutrition… because you simply cannot have one without the other.  

“Every six seconds, a child under the age of 5 dies somewhere in the world” 

Shockingly, in 2019, 6.1 million children and young adolescents died; 5.2 million of these were children under the age of 5. Preventable illnesses including diarrhoea, pneumonia, and malaria are responsible for the majority of these deaths. Malnutrition directly leads to death or further complicates these illnesses resulting in premature death. 

These deaths are avoidable. Access to affordable, quality health care alongside health and nutrition education is essential.  

Your donation is “For every child, everywhere”, thank you.

story:
Bombs, Bullets and Babies.

MS teams - March 25th - Link on FB 

MSF has been working in Afghanistan since 1980 supporting the Ministry of Health's facilities, treating patients injured during the conflict and opening maternity and childcare hospitals. The talk will discuss the issues encountered by returning refugees and the impact conflict has on hospital conditions, which severely affect maternity services.

  • £30 provides clean linen and gowns for 2 surgical operations

story:
From Manchester to Madagascar 

From 15th February, well be walking, running, cycling, rowing and swimming to travel the 5,777 miles between Manchester to Madagascar, all in aid of highlighting WaterAid's work in Antenanarivo, Madagascar.

5,777 miles might take us a while to complete, so we are going to compete in two teams and start at each end - one team in Manchester and one team in Madagascar - and the objective is to meet in the middle by Easter, and see who gets there first!

Well be walking, running, cycling, rowing or even swimming (when allowed!) to help contribute individually and virtually to the 5,777 miles we need to complete together. 

The objective is to improve all our wellbeing, get us all out more in the fresh air and away from our computers, and to raise £5,777 for a truly magnificent cause!

story:
The Fortress Fitness Challenge

At Fortress as a part of the Water for Life campaign we have set the challenge to complete a 6,214 km (3,861 mile) journey in 1 month from our UK Wolverhampton office across the Atlantic to our US office in Cincinnati, Ohio. From running to walking, cycling to swimming every mile counts and every penny counts.

You can track our progress on Charity Miles under the team name 'Fortress Fitness Challenge'.

Thank you for your support

We appreciate all the support from our Fortress team, as well as wider family and friends who are donating to create a better future and a fairer world. To give you an indication of how far this money will go—just £15 can provide one person with clean water.

WaterAid

WaterAid is working to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. The international not-for-profit organisation works in 28 countries to change the lives of the poorest and most marginalised people. Since 1981, WaterAid has reached 26.4 million people with clean water and 26.3 million people with decent toilets.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
On the 10th July I am undertaking the SEVERN TRENT MOUNTAIN CHALLENGE, throughout the Dark Peak hills and moors of the "Peak District National Park". This is a 30miles and 6000ft of climb ONE DAY TREK, recognised as one of the country’s most difficult events.  

I am raising funds for WATER AID to provide clean water and sewage facilities throughout the disadvantaged areas of the world. Having clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene SOUNDS NORMAL and IT SHOULD BE A NORMAL PART of everyone's daily life. Without all three, people can't live dignified, healthy lives.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, people do not have to drink water contaminated with animal & human waste. Children are born healthier; deadly "Waterborne infections and illnesses" are eliminated. Whole communities start to thrive.

If you can, Please Help by making a donation through this Fundraising Page and move towards giving CLEAN WATER to the world. Thank you

eventName: Beatrix is Cutting Off All her Hair!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
After five years of conflict, most of the population in Yemen needs humanitarian assistance. They have a lack of basic healthcare, severe food shortages and limited clean water. CARE is focused on helping the most vulnerable people, through distributing food to families in need, and cash vouchers so that families can purchase for themselves the food they need.Over a year of fighting and fuel shortages has destroyed water pipes and water pumping facilities, so CARE is rehabilitating water sources and providing water tanks so women and children can get safe drinking water without having to travel long distances.CARE is also providing hygiene kits, paying special attention to women's and children's needs.Thank you for reading. 

Beatrix has never had her hair cut, she'll be donating the hair to the Little Princess Trust and raising money for children in Yemen in the process.

For more information please visit the dedicated Yemen Crisis page on CARE's website: www.careinternational.org.uk/emergencies/yemen-crisis
